|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/2019/04/2019-hugo-award-1944-retro-hugo-award-finalists/|publisher=The Hugo Awards|accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[45th Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]]\n|Best Streaming Science Fiction, Action & Fantasy Series\n| data-sort-value=\"Expanse, The\" | ''The Expanse''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|title='Avengers: Endgame', 'Game of Thrones' Lead the 2019 Saturn Awards Nominations |url=http://collider.com/saturn-awards-nominations-2019/ |work=Collider |first=Vinnie |last=Mancuso |date=July 15, 2019 |accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2020\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Hugo Award]]s\n|Best Series\n|''The Expanse''| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://locusmag.com/2020/04/2020-hugo-and-astounding-awards-finalists/|title=2020 Hugo and Astounding Awards Finalists|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|Best Dramatic Presentation, Short Form\n|The Expanse: \u201c''Cibola Burn''\u201d\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.syfy.com/theexpanse|''The Expanse''}} on [[Syfy]]\n* [https://www.amazon.com/dp/B018BZ3SCM ''The Expanse''] on [[Prime Video]]\n* {{IMDb title}}\n\n{{The Expanse}}\n{{Syfy Shows}}\n{{Amazon Video original series}}\n{{Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation, Short Form}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Expanse, The}}\n[[Category:2010s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2015 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Asteroid mining in fiction]]\n[[Category:Augmented reality in fiction]]\n[[Category:Ceres (dwarf planet) in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award-winning television series]]\n[[Category:Main-belt asteroids in fiction]]\n[[Category:Mars in television]]\n[[Category:Space adventure television series]]\n[[Category:Space opera television series]]\n[[Category:Space Western television series]]\n[[Category:Neo-noir television series]]\n[[Category:Syfy original programming]]\n[[Category:Amazon Video original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series about conspiracy theories]]\n[[Category:Television series about extraterrestrial life]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Television series by Universal Television]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Toronto]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 23rd century]]\n[[Category:The Expanse| ]]\n[[Category:Water scarcity in fiction]]\n", "name_user": "Cryptic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAccolades:repair", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Expanse_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "March 10", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n*[[241 BC]] &ndash; [[First Punic War]]: [[Battle of the Aegates]]: The [[Roman Republic|Romans]] sink the [[Carthage|Carthaginian]] fleet bringing the First Punic War to an end.\n* [[298]] &ndash; Roman Emperor [[Maximian]] concludes his campaign in [[Africa (Roman province)|North Africa]] against the [[Berbers]], and makes a triumphal entry into [[Carthage]].\n* [[947]] &ndash; The [[Later Han (Five Dynasties)|Later Han]] is founded by [[Liu Zhiyuan]]. He declares himself emperor and establishes the capital in Bian, present-day [[Kaifeng]].\n*[[1607]] &ndash; [[Susenyos I]] defeats the combined armies of [[Yaqob]] and [[Abuna]] Petros II at the Battle of Gol in [[Gojjam]], making him [[Emperor of Ethiopia]].\n*[[1629]] &ndash; [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] dissolves the [[Parliament of England]], beginning the eleven-year period known as the [[Personal Rule]].\n*[[1735]] &ndash; An agreement between [[Nader Shah]] and Russia is signed near [[Ganja, Azerbaijan]] and Russian troops are withdrawn from [[Baku]].\n*[[1762]] &ndash; French [[Huguenot]] [[Jean Calas]], who had been wrongly convicted of killing his son, dies after being tortured by authorities; the event inspired [[Voltaire]] to begin a campaign for religious tolerance and legal reform.\n*[[1804]] &ndash; [[Louisiana Purchase]]: In [[St. Louis, Missouri]], a [[Three Flags Day|formal ceremony]] is conducted to transfer ownership of the [[Louisiana Territory]] from [[France]] to the [[United States]].\n*[[1814]] &ndash; Emperor [[Napoleon|Napoleon I]] is defeated at the [[Battle of Laon]] in France.\n*[[1816]] &ndash; [[Crossing of the Andes]]: A group of royalist scouts are captured during the [[Action of Juncalito]].\n*[[1830]] &ndash; The [[Royal Netherlands East Indies Army]] is created.\n*[[1848]] &ndash; The [[Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo]] is ratified by the [[United States Senate]], ending the [[Mexican\u2013American War]].\n*[[1861]] &ndash; [[El Hadj Umar Tall]] seizes the city of [[S\u00e9gou]], destroying the [[Bamana Empire]] of [[Mali]].\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[Amy Spain]], American slave, is executed for stealing from her owner; believed to have been the last legal execution of a female slave in America.\n*[[1873]] &ndash; The first Azerbaijani play \"The Adventures of the Vizier of the Khan of Lenkaran\" prepared by Akhundov was performed by [[Hasan bey Zardabi|Hassan-bey Zardabi]] and dramatist and [[Najaf bey Vazirov|Najaf-bey Vezirov]]. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.azernews.az/culture/50682.html|title=Azerbaijani theater marks 140th anniversary|date=2013-03-08|website=AzerNews.az|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.visions.az/en/news/238/7094705d/|title=Visions of Azerbaijan Magazine ::: The Azerbaijani Theatre: past to present|website=Visions of Azerbaijan Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-03-06}}</ref>\n*[[1876]] &ndash; The first successful [[Invention of the telephone|test of a telephone]] is made by [[Alexander Graham Bell]].\n*[[1891]] &ndash; [[Almon Strowger]], an undertaker in [[Topeka, Kansas]], patents the [[Strowger switch]], a device which led to the automation of telephone circuit switching.\n*[[1906]] &ndash; The [[Courri\u00e8res mine disaster]], Europe's worst ever, kills 1099 miners in northern France.\n*[[1909]] &ndash; By signing the [[Anglo-Siamese Treaty of 1909]], [[Thailand]] relinquishes its [[sovereignty]] over the [[Malay states]] of [[Kedah]], [[Kelantan]], [[Perlis]] and [[Terengganu]], which become [[British protectorates]].\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[World War I]]: The [[Battle of Neuve Chapelle]] begins. This is the first large-scale operation by the [[British Army]] in the war.\n*[[1916]] &ndash; The [[McMahon\u2013Hussein Correspondence]] between [[Hussein bin Ali, Sharif of Mecca]] and the British official [[Henry McMahon (diplomat)|Henry McMahon]] concerning the [[Arab revolt]] against the [[Ottoman Empire]] ends.\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Mahatma Gandhi]] is arrested in India, tried for [[sedition]], and sentenced to six years in prison, only to be released after nearly two years for an [[appendicitis]] operation.\n*[[1933]] &ndash; The 6.4 {{M|w}} [[1933 Long Beach earthquake|Long Beach earthquake]] affects the [[Greater Los Angeles Area]] with a maximum [[Mercalli intensity scale|Mercalli intensity]] of VIII (''Severe''), leaving 115\u2013120 people dead, and causing an estimated $40 million in damage.\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[Greek Civil War]]: The [[Political Committee of National Liberation]] is established in Greece by the [[National Liberation Front (Greece)|National Liberation Front]].\n*[[1945]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: The U.S. Army Air Force [[Bombing of Tokyo (10 March 1945)|firebombs Tokyo]], and the resulting conflagration kills more than 100,000 people, mostly civilians.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ralph |first1=William W. |title=Improvised Destruction: Arnold, LeMay, and the Firebombing of Japan |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/26061697?seq=1 |website=War in History |accessdate=24 January 2020 |pages=495\u2013522 |date=2006}}</ref>\n*[[1949]] &ndash; [[Mildred Gillars]] (\"[[Axis Sally]]\") is convicted of [[treason]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.historynet.com/mildred-elizabeth-sisk-american-born-axis-sally.htm |title=Mildred Elizabeth Sisk: American-Born Axis Sally |date=June 12, 2006 |website=HistoryNet |language=en-US |access-date=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[1952]] &ndash; [[Fulgencio Batista]] leads a successful [[coup]] in [[Cuba]] and appoints himself as the \"provisional president\".\n*[[1959]] &ndash; [[1959 Tibetan uprising|Tibetan uprising]]: Fearing an abduction attempt by China, thousands of [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]] surround the [[Dalai Lama]]'s palace to prevent his removal.\n*[[1966]] &ndash; Military Prime Minister of [[South Vietnam]] [[Nguy\u1ec5n Cao K\u1ef3]] sacked rival General [[Nguy\u1ec5n Ch\u00e1nh Thi]], precipitating [[Buddhist Uprising|large-scale civil and military dissension]] in parts of the nation.\n*[[1968]] &ndash; [[Vietnam War]]: [[Battle of Lima Site 85]], concluding the 11th with largest single ground combat loss of United States Air Force members during that war.\n*[[1969]] &ndash; In [[Memphis, Tennessee]], [[James Earl Ray]] pleads guilty to assassinating [[Martin Luther King, Jr]]. He later unsuccessfully attempts to recant.\n*[[1970]] &ndash; Vietnam War: Captain [[Ernest Medina]] is charged by the U.S. military with [[My Lai Massacre|My Lai war crimes]].\n*[[1975]] &ndash; Vietnam War: [[1975 Spring Offensive|Ho Chi Minh Campaign]]: [[North Vietnam]]ese troops [[Battle of Ban Me Thuot|attack Ban M\u00ea Thu\u1ed9t]] in the South on their way to capturing [[Saigon]] in the final push for victory over South Vietnam.\n*[[1977]] &ndash; Astronomers discover the [[rings of Uranus]].\n*[[1990]] &ndash; In [[Haiti]], [[Prosper Avril]] is ousted 18 months after seizing power in a [[coup]].\n*[[2000]] &ndash; The [[Nasdaq Composite]] [[stock market index]] peaks at 5132.52, signaling the beginning of the end of the [[dot-com bubble|dot-com boom]].\n*[[2006]] &ndash; The [[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]] arrives at [[Mars]].\n*[[2017]] &ndash; The [[Impeachment of Park Geun-hye|impeachment]] of [[President of South Korea|President]] [[Park Geun-hye]] of [[South Korea]] in response to a [[2016 South Korean political scandal|major political scandal]] is unanimously upheld by the country's [[Constitutional Court of Korea|Constitutional Court]], ending her presidency.\n*[[2019]] &ndash; [[Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302]], a [[Boeing]] [[737 MAX]], crashes, leading to all 737 MAX aircraft being grounded worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Amiri |first1=Farnoush |last2=Kesslen |first2=Ben |title=Boeing 737 Max jets grounded by FAA emergency order |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/boeing-s-737-max-jets-now-grounded-canada-well-europe-n982811 |website=NBC News |publisher=NBC |accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Births==\n* [[852]] &ndash; [[Qian Liu]], Chinese warlord and king (d. 932)\n*[[1415]] &ndash; [[Vasily II of Moscow|Vasily II]], Grand Prince of Moscow (d. 1462)\n*[[1430]] &ndash; [[Oliviero Carafa]], Catholic cardinal (d. 1511)\n*[[1452]] &ndash; [[Ferdinand II of Aragon|Ferdinand II]], king of [[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]] and [[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n|Le\u00f3n]] (d. 1516)\n*[[1503]] &ndash; [[Ferdinand I, Holy Roman Emperor]] (d. 1564)\n*[[1536]] &ndash; [[Thomas Howard, 4th Duke of Norfolk]], English politician, [[Earl Marshal|Earl Marshal of the United Kingdom]] (d. 1572)\n*[[1549]] &ndash; [[Francis Solanus]], Spanish missionary and saint (d. 1610)\n*[[1590]] &ndash; [[Dietrich Reinkingk]], German lawyer and politician (d. 1664)\n*[[1604]] &ndash; [[Johann Rudolf Glauber]], German-Dutch alchemist and chemist (d. 1670)\n*[[1607]] &ndash; [[Thomas Wriothesley, 4th Earl of Southampton]], English statesman (d. 1667)\n*[[1628]] &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois Girardon]], French sculptor (d. 1715)\n*  1628   &ndash; [[Marcello Malpighi]], Italian physician and biologist (d. 1694)\n*[[1652]] &ndash; [[Giacomo Serpotta]], Italian Rococo sculptor (d. 1732)\n*[[1653]] &ndash; [[John Benbow]], Royal Navy admiral (d. 1702)\n*[[1709]] &ndash; [[Georg Wilhelm Steller]], German botanist, zoologist, physician, and explorer (d. 1746)\n*[[1745]] &ndash; [[John Gunby]], American general (d. 1807)\n*[[1749]] &ndash; [[Lorenzo Da Ponte]], Italian-American priest and poet (d. 1838)\n*[[1769]] &ndash; [[Joseph Williamson (philanthropist)|Joseph Williamson]], English businessman and philanthropist (d. 1840)\n*[[1772]] &ndash; [[Karl Wilhelm Friedrich Schlegel]], German poet and critic (d. 1829)\n*[[1777]] &ndash; [[Louis Hersent]], French painter (d. 1860)\n*[[1787]] &ndash; [[Francisco de Paula Mart\u00ednez de la Rosa y Berdejo]], Spanish playwright and politician, [[Prime Minister of Spain]] (d. 1862)\n*  1787   &ndash; [[William Etty]], English painter and academic (d. 1849)\n*[[1788]] &ndash; [[Joseph Freiherr von Eichendorff]], German author, poet, playwright, and critic (d. 1857)\n*  1788   &ndash; [[Edward Hodges Baily]], English sculptor (d. 1867)\n*[[1789]] &ndash; [[Manuel de la Pe\u00f1a y Pe\u00f1a]], Mexican lawyer and 20th President (1847) (d. 1850)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://presidentes.mx/manuel-de-la-pena-y-pena|publisher=Presidencia de la Republica de Mexico|title=Manuel de la Pe\u00f1a y Pe\u00f1a|language=Spanish|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref> \n*[[1795]] &ndash; [[Joseph L\u00e9gar\u00e9]], Canadian painter and glazier, artist, seigneur and political figure (d. 1855)\n*[[1810]] &ndash; [[Samuel Ferguson]], Irish poet and lawyer (d. 1886)\n*[[1844]] &ndash; [[Pablo de Sarasate]], Spanish violinist and composer (d. 1908)\n*  1844   &ndash; [[Marie Spartali Stillman|Marie Euphrosyne Spartali]], British Pre-Raphaelite painter (d. 1927)\n*[[1845]] &ndash; [[Alexander III of Russia]] (d. 1894)\n*[[1846]] &ndash; [[Edward Baker Lincoln]], American son of [[Abraham Lincoln]] (d. 1850)\n*[[1849]] &ndash; [[Hallie Quinn Brown]], African-American educator, writer and activist (d. 1949)\n*[[1850]] &ndash; [[Spencer Gore (sportsman)|Spencer Gore]], English tennis player and cricketer (d. 1906)\n*[[1853]] &ndash; [[Thomas Mackenzie]], Scottish-New Zealand cartographer and politician, 18th [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] (d. 1930)\n*[[1864]] &ndash; [[\u0100dams Alksnis]], Latvian painter (d. 1897)\n*[[1867]] &ndash; [[Hector Guimard]], French-American architect, designed the [[La Bluette]] (d. 1942)\n*  1867   &ndash; [[Lillian Wald]], American nurse, humanitarian, and author, founded the [[Henry Street Settlement]] (d. 1940)\n*[[1870]] &ndash; [[David Riazanov]], Russian theorist and politician (d. 1938)\n*[[1873]] &ndash; [[Jakob Wassermann]], German-Austrian soldier and author (d. 1934)\n*[[1876]] &ndash; [[Edvard Eriksen]], Danish-Icelandic sculptor and woodcarver (d. 1959)\n*  1876   &ndash; [[Anna Hyatt Huntington]], American sculptor (d. 1973)\n*[[1877]] &ndash; [[Pascual Ortiz Rubio]], Mexican diplomat and president (1930-1932) (d. 1963) \n*[[1881]] &ndash; [[Jessie Boswell]], English painter (d. 1956)\n*[[1885]] &ndash; [[Tamara Karsavina]], Russian-English ballerina and educator (d. 1978)\n*[[1888]] &ndash; [[Barry Fitzgerald]], Irish actor (d. 1961)\n*[[1889]] &ndash; [[Toshitsugu Takamatsu]], Japanese martial artist and educator (d. 1972)\n*[[1890]] &ndash; [[Gakury\u014d Nakamura]], Japanese painter and designer (d. 1969)\n*  1890   &ndash; [[Albert Ogilvie]], Australian politician, 28th [[Premier of Tasmania]] (d. 1939)\n*[[1891]] &ndash; [[Sam Jaffe]], American actor and engineer (d. 1984)\n*[[1892]] &ndash; [[Arthur Honegger]], French-Swiss composer and educator (d. 1955)\n*  1892   &ndash; [[Gregory La Cava]], American director, producer, and screenwriter (d. 1952)\n*[[1896]] &ndash; [[Coulton Waugh|Frederick Coulton Waugh]], British cartoonist, painter, teacher and author (d. 1973)\n*[[1900]] &ndash; [[Violet Brown]], Jamaican supercentenarian, oldest Jamaican ever (d. 2017) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.grg.org/SC/WorldSCRankingsList.html|title=GRG World Supercentenarian Rankings List|website=www.grg.org|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> \n*  1900   &ndash; [[Pandelis Pouliopoulos]], Greek lawyer and politician (d. 1943) \n*[[1901]] &ndash; [[Michel Seuphor]], Belgian painter (d. 1999)\n*[[1903]] &ndash; [[Bix Beiderbecke]], American cornet player, pianist, and composer (d. 1931)\n*  1903   &ndash; [[Clare Boothe Luce]], American playwright, journalist, and diplomat, [[United States Ambassador to Italy]] (d. 1987)\n*  1903   &ndash; [[Edward Bawden]], British artist and illustrator (d. 1989)\n*[[1914]] &ndash; [[Chandler Harper]], American golfer (d. 2004)\n*  1914   &ndash; [[K. P. Ratnam]], Sri Lankan academic and politician (d. 2010)\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Harry Bertoia]], Italian-American sculptor and furniture designer (d. 1978) \n*  1915   &ndash; [[Jo\u017ea Horvat]], Croatian writer (d. 2012) \n*[[1916]] &ndash; [[Davie Fulton]], Canadian lawyer, judge, and politician (d. 2000)\n*[[1917]] &ndash; [[David Hare (artist)|David Hare]], American Surrealist artist, sculptor, photographer and painter (d. 1992)\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[G\u00fcnther Rall]], German general and pilot (d. 2009)\n*[[1919]] &ndash; [[Marion Hutton]], American singer and actress (d. 1987)\n*[[1920]] &ndash; [[Alfred Peet]], Dutch-American businessman, founded [[Peet's Coffee & Tea]] (d. 2007)\n*  1920   &ndash; [[Boris Vian]], French author and playwright (d. 1959)\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Kiyoshi Yamashita]], Japanese painter (d. 1971)\n*[[1923]] &ndash; [[Val Logsdon Fitch]], American physicist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. 2015)\n*[[1924]] &ndash; [[Judith Jones]], American literary and cookbook editor (d. 2017)\n*  1925   &ndash; [[Bob Lanier (politician)|Bob Lanier]], American lawyer, banker, and politician, 58th [[List of mayors of Houston|Mayor of Houston]] (d. 2014)\n*[[1926]] &ndash; [[Marques Haynes]], American basketball player (d. 2015)\n*[[1927]] &ndash; [[Claude Laydu]], Belgian-French actor, producer, and screenwriter (d. 2011)\n*  1927   &ndash; [[Paul Wunderlich]],  German painter, sculptor and graphic artist (d. 2010)\n*[[1928]] &ndash; [[Sara Montiel]], Spanish actress (d. 2013)\n*  1928   &ndash; [[James Earl Ray]], American criminal; assassin of Martin Luther King Jr. (d. 1998)\n*[[1929]] &ndash; [[Sam Steiger]], American journalist and politician (d. 2012)\n*[[1930]] &ndash; [[S\u00e1ndor Iharos]], Hungarian runner (d. 1996)\n*[[1931]] &ndash; [[Georges Dor]], Canadian author, playwright, and composer (d. 2001)\n*[[1932]] &ndash; [[Marcia Falkender, Baroness Falkender]], English politician (d. 2019)\n*  1932   &ndash; [[Udupi Ramachandra Rao]], Indian physicist and engineer (d. 2017)\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Perunchithi