 Loggia, Scott Bakula\n*''[[Geronimo (film)|Geronimo]]'', TNT: Joseph Runningfox\n*''[[Zelda (film)|Zelda]]'', TNT: Natasha Richardson, Timothy Hutton\n*''[[Murder in the Heartland]]'', Tim Roth, Fairuza Balk\n*''[[List of Hallmark Hall of Fame episodes#Season 42 (1992-1993)|Blind Spot]]'', Hallmark Hall of Fame \u2013 CBS: Joanne Woodward, Laura Linney\n*''[[Jewels (miniseries)|Jewels]]'', CBS: Annette O'Toole, Anthony Andrews\n*''[[In Broad Daylight (1991 film)|In Broad Daylight]]'', NBC: Brian Dennehy, Marcia Gay Harden\n*''[[Her Hidden Truth]]', NBC: Kellie Martin, Antonio Sabato Jr.\n\n==Television series credits==\nThis is a partial list.\n\n*''[[Monk (TV series)|Monk]]''\n*''Extreme''\n*''Black Tie Affair''\n*''Baltimore''\n*''Cutters''\n*''[[The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd]]'' (theme and episode scores)\n*''[[The Simpsons]]'': \"[[Simpson and Delilah]]\"\n*''[[The Slap Maxwell Story]]''\n*''FM''\n*''[[AfterMASH]]''\n*''[[Columbo (TV series)|Columbo]]''\n*''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]''\n*''[[The Streets of San Francisco]]'' (theme and 11 scores)\n*''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]''\n*''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]''\n*''[[The Tony Randall Show]]''\n*''[[The Magician (U.S. TV series)|The Magician]]''\n*''[[Hercules (TV miniseries)|Hercules]]''\n*''[[The Music Scene (TV series)|The Music Scene]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.patrickwilliamsmusic.com/}}\n*{{Allmusic |class=artist |id=patrick-williams-mn0000016620}}\n*{{Discogs artist|255279-Patrick-Williams|Patrick Williams}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0002305|name=Patrick Williams}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:American classical musicians]]\n[[Category:American film score composers]]\n[[Category:American male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:American music arrangers]]\n[[Category:American television composers]]\n[[Category:Classical musicians from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Classical musicians from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Easy listening musicians]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:Male television composers]]\n[[Category:People from Bonne Terre, Missouri]]\n", "name_user": "DemonDays64", "label": "safe", "comment": "Importing Wikidatashort description: \"Composer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Williams_(composer)"}
{"title_page": "John Fiedler", "text_new": "{{distinguish|John Fielder}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Fiedler\n| image         = John Fiedler.png\n| caption       = Fiedler in the ''Star Trek'' episode<br>\"[[Wolf in the Fold]]\"\n| birth_name     = John Donald Fiedler\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1925|02|03}}\n| birth_place    = [[Platteville, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|2005|06|25|1925|02|03}}\n| death_place    = [[Englewood, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actor, voice actor\n| years active  = 1949\u20132005\n}}\n[[File:A Raisin in the Sun 1959.JPG|thumb|250px|From the Broadway play ''[[Raisin in the Sun]]''. L-R: [[Ruby Dee]], [[Claudia McNeil]], [[Glynn Turman]], [[Sidney Poitier]], and John Fiedler (1959)]]\n'''John Donald Fiedler''' (February 3, 1925 \u2013 June 25, 2005) was an American actor and voice actor, who was slight, balding, and bespectacled, with a distinctive, high-pitched voice. His career lasted more than 55 years in [[stage (theatre)|stage]], [[film]], [[television]] and [[radio programming|radio]]. Among his best-known roles are the nervous Juror #2 in ''[[12 Angry Men (1957 film)|12 Angry Men]]'' (1957); the benign-seeming gentleman who tries to prevent the Younger family from moving into a whites-only neighbourhood in [[A Raisin in the Sun (1961 film)|''A Raisin in the Sun'']] (1961); the voice of [[Piglet (Winnie-the-Pooh)|Piglet]] in [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]'s [[Winnie-the-Pooh]] productions; Vinnie, one of Oscar's poker buddies in the film ''[[The Odd Couple (film)|The Odd Couple]]'' (1968); the government official who gets possessed by the spirit of [[Jack the Ripper]] on the ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' episode \"Wolf in the Fold\" (1967), and Mr. Emil Peterson, the hen-pecked husband on ''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nFiedler was born in [[Platteville, Wisconsin]], a son of Donald Fiedler, a beer salesman, and his wife Margaret (n\u00e9e Phelan).<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/0/John-Fiedler.html John Fiedler profile], filmreference.com; accessed November 30, 2015.</ref> He was of German and Irish descent.<ref>{{cite news| title=John Fiedler, 80; Character Actor Best Known for Distinctive Voice| url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-jun-28-me-fiedler28-story.html| last=McLellan| first=Dennis| date=28 June 2005| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis family moved to [[Shorewood, Wisconsin]] in 1930, where he graduated from [[Shorewood High School (Wisconsin)|Shorewood High School]] in 1943. He enlisted in the [[United States Navy]] and served until the end of [[World War II]].<ref>O'Donnell, Michelle. [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/27/movies/27fiedler.html \"John Fiedler, 80, Stage Actor and Film Voice of Pooh's Piglet, Dies\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 27, 2005; accessed December 15, 2007. \"He graduated from Shorewood High School in 1943 and enlisted in the United States Navy, serving stateside until World War II's end.\"</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2015}}\nAfter his discharge from the Navy, Fiedler began acting in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], appearing on the [[radio comedy]] ''[[The Aldrich Family]]'' as Homer Brown. He appeared on early television and played Cadet Alfie Higgins on the 1950s show ''[[Tom Corbett, Space Cadet]]'', and he made his film debut in ''[[12 Angry Men (1957 film)|12 Angry Men]]'' (1957), as Juror #2. Most of his roles were playing gentle or nervous individuals, though he appeared as the lawyer J. Noble Daggett in ''[[True Grit (1969 film)|True Grit]]'' (1969) and in the original ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' episode \"[[Wolf in the Fold]]\" (1967) as Mr. Hengist, a Chief Administrator possessed by the spirit of [[Jack the Ripper]].\n\nFiedler was in the original cast of ''[[A Raisin in the Sun]]'' as housing committee representative Lindner, a role he also played in both the [[A Raisin in the Sun (1961 film)|1961 film version]] and the 1988 TV version. He appeared in the film ''[[The Odd Couple (film)|The Odd Couple]]'' (1968) as [[poker]] player Vinnie; he also appeared on the TV series adaptation ''[[The Odd Couple (1970 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]'', at the invitation of his friend [[Jack Klugman]], as the manager of a hyper-security building into which Felix and Oscar temporarily moved and the owner of a racing greyhound adopted by Felix and Oscar. He also appeared in the films ''[[Harper Valley PTA (film)|Harper Valley PTA]]'' (1978) and ''[[The Cannonball Run]]'' (1981).\n\nHe appeared three times in a recurring role on ''[[Kolchak: The Night Stalker]]'' as [[morgue]] attendant Gordy \"The Ghoul\" Spangler. He also played Mr. Peterson, one of Bob's regular patients, on ''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]'', and Mr. Dundee in an episode of the ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|Twilight Zone]]'', \"[[The Night of the Meek]]\" (1960). His many other guest appearances on TV included ''[[Columbo]]'', ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'', ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', ''[[Bonanza]]'', ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', ''[[My Favorite Martian]]'', ''[[Bewitched]]'', ''[[Get Smart]]'', ''[[A Touch of Grace]]'', ''[[The Rockford Files]]'', ''[[Quincy, M.E.]]'', ''[[The Golden Girls]]'', ''[[Banacek]]'' and ''[[Cheers]]''. He also appeared in ''[[The Munsters]]''. Fielder was also cast against type in the Star Trek episode [[Wolf in the Fold]], where he played \nAdministrator Hengist, who was harboring the soul of a serial killer and had been murdering several women on the planet Argelius II.\n\nFiedler worked frequently for [[Walt Disney Productions]]. His voice was heard in the Disney features ''[[Robin Hood (1973 film)|Robin Hood]]'' (1973), ''[[The Rescuers]]'' (1976), ''[[The Fox and the Hound (film)|The Fox and the Hound]]'' (1981), and ''[[The Emperor's New Groove]]'' (2000), and in [[Disneyland Records]]' ''Winnie the Pooh for President''. He voiced the character Piglet for the studio's ''[[The Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh]]'' (1977), ''[[The Tigger Movie]]'' (2000), ''[[Piglet's Big Movie]]'' (2003), ''[[Pooh's Heffalump Movie]]'' (2005). He  appeared in Disney's live-action films ''[[Rascal (film)|Rascal]]'' (1969) and ''[[The Shaggy D.A.]]'' (1976).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://cartoonresearch.com/index.php/winnie-the-pooh-for-president/| title=Winnie the Pooh for President| website=Cartoon Research| date=2 August 2016| accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref> His last film was a voice appearance in ''[[Kronk's New Groove]]'' (2005) and in the [[Square Enix]]/Disney video game ''[[Kingdom Hearts (video game)|Kingdom Hearts]]''. Fiedler was also the narrator of several [[McDonaldland]] commercials during the 1980s, including when Birdie the Early Bird learns to fly and how the Hamburglar got his stripes.\n\n==Death==\nFiedler died of [[cancer]] on June 25, 2005, in [[Englewood, New Jersey]], at the [[Lillian Booth Actors Home]], a residence for retired entertainers sponsored by the [[Actors' Fund of America]]. Fiedler's friend and ''Winnie-the-Pooh'' co-star, [[Paul Winchell]],  who voiced [[Tigger]], died the previous day due to [[natural causes]].<ref>{{cite news| title=Paul Winchell, 82; the Voice of Tigger Gained Fame as Ventriloquist| url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-jun-26-me-winchell26-story.html| last=Oliver| first=Myrna| date=25 June 2005| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref> Fiedler was cremated and his ashes were scattered on [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. [[Travis Oates]] has since replaced Fiedler as the voice of Piglet.<ref>Bernstein, Adam. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/06/27/AR2005062701569.html \"Actor John Fiedler Dies; Was Piglet's Voice in 'Pooh' Films\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]''. June 28, 2005. Accessed December 15, 2007. \"John Fiedler, 80, a stage, film and television actor who excelled at meek or nervous roles and was personally chosen by Walt Disney to play the voice of Piglet in Winnie the Pooh films, died June 25 at the Lillian Booth Actors' Home in Englewood, N.J.\"</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''[[12 Angry Men (1957 film)|12 Angry Men]]'' (1957) as Juror #2\n*''[[Sweet Smell of Success]]'' (1957) as Counterman at Hot Dog Stand (uncredited)\n*''[[Stage Struck (1958 film)|Stage Struck]]'' (1958) as Adrian\n*''[[That Kind of Woman]]'' (1959) as Eager Soldier (uncredited)\n*''[[A Raisin in the Sun (1961 film)|A Raisin in the Sun]] '' (1961) as Karl Lindner\n*''[[That Touch of Mink]]'' (1962) as Mr. Smith\n*''[[The World of Henry Orient]]'' (1964) as Sidney\n*''[[Kiss Me, Stupid]]'' (1964) as Rev. Carruthers\n*''[[Guns of Diablo]]'' (1965) as Ives\n*''[[Girl Happy]]'' (1965) as Mr. Penchill\n*''[[A Fine Madness]]'' (1966) as Daniel K. Papp\n*''[[The Ballad of Josie]]'' (1967) as Simpson\n*''[[Fitzwilly]]'' (1967) as Mr. Morton Dunne\n*''[[The Odd Couple (film)|The Odd Couple]]'' (1968) as Vinnie\n*''[[Winnie the Pooh and the Blustery Day]]'' (1968) as Piglet (voice)\n*''[[Rascal (film)|Rascal]]'' (1969) as Cy Jenkins\n*''[[True Grit (1969 film)|True Grit]]'' (1969) as Lawyer Daggett\n*''[[The Great Bank Robbery (1969 film)|The Great Bank Robbery]]'' (1969) as Brother Dismas Ostracorn - Explosives\n*''[[Suppose They Gave a War and Nobody Came]]'' (1970) as Maj. Purvis\n*''[[Making It (film)|Making It]]'' (1971) as Ames\n*''Honky'' (1971)\n*''[[Skyjacked (film)|Skyjacked]]'' (1972) as Robert Grandig\n*''Deathmaster'' (1972) as Pop\n*''[[Robin Hood (1973 film)|Robin Hood]]'' (1973) as Father Sexton (voice, uncredited)\n*''[[Winnie the Pooh and Tigger Too]]'' (1974) as Piglet (voice)\n*''[[The Fortune]]'' (1975) as Photographer\n*''[[The Shaggy D.A.]]'' (1976) as Howie Clemmings\n*''[[The Many Adventures of Winnie-the-Pooh]]'' (1977) as Piglet (voice)\n*''[[The Rescuers]]'' (1977) as Deacon 