{"title_page": "Patrick Williams (cricketer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|English cricketer and British Army officer}}\n{{other people|Patrick Williams|Patrick Williams}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = \n|               image = \n|             country = England\n|            fullname =\tPatrick Cyril Williams\n|          birth_date = 12 December 1912\n|         birth_place = [[Ningbo|Ningpo]], [[Chekiang Province, Republic of China|Chekiang Province]], [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|China]]\n|          death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1981|12|9|1912|12|12}}\n|         death_place = [[Helston]], [[Cornwall]], England\n|            nickname = \n|              family = \n|             batting = Unknown\n|             bowling = Unknown\n|                role = \n|               club1 = [[Europeans cricket team|Europeans]]\n|               year1 = 1940/41\n|               club2 = [[Wiltshire County Cricket Club|Wiltshire]]\n|               year2 = 1947\n|             columns = 1\n|             column1 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n|            matches1 = 1\n|               runs1 = 14\n|            bat avg1 = 7.00\n|           100s/50s1 = \u2013/\u2013\n|          top score1 = 14\n|         deliveries1 = 172\n|            wickets1 = 3\n|           bowl avg1 = 29.33\n|            fivefor1 = 1\n|             tenfor1 = \u2013\n|       best bowling1 = 3/88\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 1/\u2013\n|                date = 26 June \n|                year = 2019\n|              source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/35976.html Cricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Cyril Williams''' {{postnominal|OBE}} (12 December 1912 &ndash; 9 December 1981) was an [[English people|English]] first-class [[cricket]]er and an officer in both the [[British Army]]. Williams served in the [[Royal Corps of Signals]] from 1933&ndash;64, during which time he was recognised for his contribution to the [[Malayan Emergency|Malayan campaign]]. He played [[first-class cricket]] while stationed in [[British India]] during the [[Second World War]].\n\n==Life and military career==\nWilliams was born at [[Ningbo|Ningpo]] in the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] in December 1912. He attended the [[Royal Military Academy, Woolwich|Royal Military Academy]] in England, graduating in February 1933 and entering into the [[Royal Corps of Signals]] as a [[Second_lieutenant#United_Kingdom_&_other_Commonwealth_countries|second lieutenant]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33908|date=3 February 1933|page=742}}</ref> He was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] in February 1936.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34252|date=4 February 1936|page=733|supp=y}}</ref> He served with the Royal Army Signal Corps during the [[Second World War]], during which he was promoted to the rank of [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in February 1941.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=35063|date=31 January 1941|page=675|supp=y}}</ref> While stationed in [[British India]] in December 1940, Williams made a single appearance in [[first-class cricket]] for the [[Europeans cricket team|Europeans]] against [[The Rest cricket team|The Rest]] at [[Brabourne Stadium|Bombay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/14/14916/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-Class Matches played by Patrick Williams |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=26 June 2019 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Batting twice in the match, he was dismissed for 14 runs in the Europeans first-innings by [[Grimley Richards]], while in their second-innings he was dismissed [[duck (cricket)|without scoring]] by [[W. L. Mascarenhas]]. With the ball he took 3 wickets in The Rest's first-innings, taking figures of 3 for 88.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/17/17288.html |title=Europeans v The Rest, 1940/41|publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=26 June 2019 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> \n\nJust under a year after the conclusion of the war, he was promoted to the rank of [[Major (British Army and Royal Marines)|major]] in July 1946.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=37635|date=28 July 1946|page=3370|supp=y}}</ref> Williams played [[Minor Counties of English and Welsh cricket|minor counties cricket]] for [[Wiltshire County Cricket Club|Wiltshire]] upon his return from duty, making a single appearance in the 1947 [[Minor Counties Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/14/14916/Minor_Counties_Championship_Matches.html |title=Minor Counties Championship Matches played by Patrick Williams |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=26 June 2019 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> He was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant colonel]] in April 1954.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=40300|date=12 October 1954|page=5831|supp=y}}</ref> He was made an [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] in December 1957, in recognition of his service during the [[Malayan Emergency]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41257|date=17 December 1957|page=7427|supp=y}}</ref> He was  promoted to the rank of [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|colonel]] in November 1985.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41550|date=14 November 1958|page=7047|supp=y}}</ref> He retired from active service in July 1964.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=43396|date=28 July 1964|page=6495|supp=y}}</ref> He died in December 1981 at [[Helston|Helston, Cornwall]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cricinfo|id=35976}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1981 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ningbo]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]]\n[[Category:Royal Corps of Signals officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Europeans cricketers]]\n[[Category:Wiltshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Malayan Emergency]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English cricketer and British Army officer}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = \n|               image = \n|             country = England\n|            fullname =\tPatrick Cyril Williams\n|          birth_date = 12 December 1912\n|         birth_place = [[Ningbo|Ningpo]], [[Chekiang Province, Republic of China|Chekiang Province]], [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|China]]\n|          death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1981|12|9|1912|12|12}}\n|         death_place = [[Helston]], [[Cornwall]], England\n|            nickname = \n|              family = \n|             batting = Unknown\n|             bowling = Unknown\n|                role = \n|               club1 = [[Europeans cricket team|Europeans]]\n|               year1 = 1940/41\n|               club2 = [[Wiltshire County Cricket Club|Wiltshire]]\n|               year2 = 1947\n|             columns = 1\n|             column1 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n|            matches1 = 1\n|               runs1 = 14\n|            bat avg1 = 7.00\n|           100s/50s1 = \u2013/\u2013\n|          top score1 = 14\n|         deliveries1 = 172\n|            wickets1 = 3\n|           bowl avg1 = 29.33\n|            fivefor1 = 1\n|             tenfor1 = \u2013\n|       best bowling1 = 3/88\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 1/\u2013\n|                date = 26 June \n|                year = 2019\n|              source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/35976.html Cricinfo\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Cyril Williams''' {{postnominal|OBE}} (12 December 1912 &ndash; 9 December 1981) was an [[English people|English]] first-class [[cricket]]er and an officer in both the [[British Army]]. Williams served in the [[Royal Corps of Signals]] from 1933&ndash;64, during which time he was recognised for his contribution to the [[Malayan Emergency|Malayan campaign]]. He played [[first-class cricket]] while stationed in [[British India]] during the [[Second World War]].\n\n==Life and military career==\nWilliams was born at [[Ningbo|Ningpo]] in the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] in December 1912. He attended the [[Royal Military Academy, Woolwich|Royal Military Academy]] in England, graduating in February 1933 and entering into the [[Royal Corps of Signals]] as a [[Second_lieutenant#United_Kingdom_&_other_Commonwealth_countries|second lieutenant]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33908|date=3 February 1933|page=742}}</ref> He was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] in February 1936.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34252|date=4 February 1936|page=733|supp=y}}</ref> He served with the Royal Army Signal Corps during the [[Second World War]], during which he was promoted to the rank of [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in February 1941.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=35063|date=31 January 1941|page=675|supp=y}}</ref> While stationed in [[British India]] in December 1940, Williams made a single appearance in [[first-class cricket]] for the [[Europeans cricket team|Europeans]] against [[The Rest cricket team|The Rest]] at [[Brabourne Stadium|Bombay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/14/14916/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-Class Matches played by Patrick Williams |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2019-06-26 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Batting twice in the match, he was dismissed for 14 runs in the Europeans first-innings by [[Grimley Richards]], while in their second-innings he was dismissed [[duck (cricket)|without scoring]] by [[W. L. Mascarenhas]]. With the ball he took 3 wickets in The Rest's first-innings, taking figures of 3 for 88.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/17/17288.html |title=Europeans v The Rest, 1940/41|publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2019-06-26 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> \n\nJust under a year after the conclusion of the war, he was promoted to the rank of [[Major (British Army and Royal Marines)|major]] in July 1946.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=37635|date=28 July 1946|page=3370|supp=y}}</ref> Williams played [[Minor Counties of English and Welsh cricket|minor counties cricket]] for [[Wiltshire County Cricket Club|Wiltshire]] upon his return from duty, making a single appearance in the 1947 [[Minor Counties Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/14/14916/Minor_Counties_Championship_Matches.html |title=Minor Counties Championship Matches played by Patrick Williams |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2019-06-26 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> He was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant colonel]] in April 1954.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=40300|date=12 October 1954|page=5831|supp=y}}</ref> He was made an [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] in December 1957, in recognition of his service during the [[Malayan Emergency]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41257|date=17 December 1957|page=7427|supp=y}}</ref> He was  promoted to the rank of [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|colonel]] in November 1985.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41550|date=14 November 1958|page=7047|supp=y}}</ref> He retired from active service in July 1964.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=43396|date=28 July 1964|page=6495|supp=y}}</ref> He died in December 1981 at [[Helston|Helston, Cornwall]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cricinfo|id=35976}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1981 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ningbo]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy, Woolwich]]\n[[Category:Royal Corps of Signals officers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Europeans cricketers]]\n[[Category:Wiltshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of the Malayan Emergency]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "name_user": "DemonDays64", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambig, EngvarB, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Williams_(cricketer)"}
{"title_page": "Max Lucado", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Max Lucado\n| image = Max Lucado portrait.jpg\n| caption = Max Lucado in 2005\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1955|1|11}}\n| birth_name = \n| birth_place = [[San Angelo, Texas]]\n| occupation = Author, Pastor, Speaker\n| years active = 1985\u2013present\n| genre = Inspirational Christian Living, Children's\n| movement = \n| notableworks = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = [[Gold Medallion Book Award]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.maxlucado.com}}\n| spouse = Denalyn Lucado\n| children = Jenna Lucado <br />Andrea Lucado <br />Sara Lucado\n| alma_mater = [[Abilene Christian University]]\n}}\n'''Max Lucado''' (born January 11, 1955) is a best-selling Christian author<ref name=christianbook>[http://www.christianbook.com/html/authors/1.html CBD Profile - Max Lucado] \"Lucado set a record by concurrently placing seven different Word titles on the CBA hardcover bestseller list in March and April 1997. In 1994, Lucado became the only author to have 11 of his 12 books in print simultaneously appear on paperback, hardcover and children\u2019s CBA bestseller lists. A Max Lucado title has appeared on the CBA hardcover bestseller list every month for the last seven years.\"</ref> and pastor at Oak Hills Church (formerly the Oak Hills Church of Christ) in [[San Antonio, Texas]].\n\n==Life==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2017}}\n\nLucado was born in [[San Angelo, Texas]], the youngest of four children to Jack and Thelma Lucado. He grew up in [[Andrews, Texas]]. His father was an oil field worker, while his mother served as a nurse.{{fact|date=December 2017}}\n\nLucado attended [[Abilene Christian University]] where he received an undergraduate degree in [[Mass Communication]]. While a student at Abilene Christian, Lucado worked to pay his way through college by selling books door-to-door with the [[Southwestern Advantage]] entrepreneurial program<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web |title=Several Famous People Held This Trying Summer Job |url=https://www.npr.org/2011/07/15/138168596/several-famous-people-held-this-trying-summer-job |website=npr.org |publisher=npr.org |accessdate=15 July 2011}}</ref>. Initially he wished to become a lawyer, but has said that a required Bible course at the university and a mission trip made him change his mind, deciding instead to become a missionary. However, this required that Lucado get a graduate degree in Bible and Biblical Studies; and, have at least two years experience ministering to a church. Lucado graduated from Abilene Christian University with a master's degree in Bible and Biblical Studies.\n\nAfter graduation, Lucado became an associate minister at Central Church of Christ in [[Miami, Florida]]. His responsibilities initially included overseeing a singles' group and writing a column for the church's newsletter. After two years in Miami, the now newlywed Lucado and his wife, Denalyn Lucado, moved to [[Rio de Janeiro, Brazil]] to become full-time missionaries. In 1987, Lucado's father died from [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis|Lou Gehrig's disease]]. After five years in Brazil, he brought his family back to the United States to be closer to his mother.\n\nMax and his wife appeared on ''[[Fixer Upper (TV series)|Fixer Upper]]'' (S3 E9 which aired January 26, 2016) when his daughter Sara and her husband Jeff Jones purchased a home that was to be remodeled by Chip & Joanna Gaines.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Basham |first=Megan |date=February 2, 2016 |title=Fixer Upper launches Christian revolution at HGTV |url=https://world.wng.org/2016/02/fixer_upper_launches_christian_revolution_at_hgtv |magazine=WORLD Magazine |access-date=March 30, 2020 }}</ref> Max asked that a quote that he had written for his daughter\u2019s wedding when he officiated be incorporated in some way into the new home without the couple knowing ahead of time. The quote was '''\u201cWould you take these two of dust and bone, born of flesh, then would you make them one? Would you speak again the words you spoke when Adam slept and Eve Awoke? Would you let your wine replace our water and look with grace on this son, this daughter? Oh Lord of Eden in your majesty create again your tapestry. One heart where there were two. This is the prayer we lift to you.\u201d''' Joanna asked Clayton Thompson to make the wall art and it was placed in the \"moffice\" (the mudroom and office combined).\n\n==Oak Hills Church==\nIn 1988, he was hired as a [[Minister (Christianity)|minister]] to the Oak Hills Church of Christ in [[San Antonio, Texas]].<ref name=\"xchron0507\"/> He stopped taking a salary from the church in 1990, because he was already an established successful author<ref name=christianbook/>.\n\nDuring his tenure, Oak Hills began using musical instruments in worship services and held the belief that baptism isn't required for salvation (two key doctrines of the [[Churches of Christ]]); ultimately Oak Hills dropped its affiliation with them in 2003, calling itself simply \"Oak Hills Church\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpnews.net/20752/max-lucado-transcends-church-of-christ-beliefs|title=Max Lucado transcends Church of Christ beliefs|first=Michael|last=Foust|website=www.bpnews.net|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2004/march/36.62.html|title=An Unusual Church of Christ|publisher=|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local_news/article/2-sets-of-hands-on-reins-3850612.php|title=Leader of the future already in position at Oak Hills Church|publisher=|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving as the senior minister at Oak Hills Church in San Antonio, TX for 20 years, Lucado announced in early 2007 that he was stepping down due to health concerns related to [[atrial fibrillation]].<ref name=\"xchron0507\">[http://www.christianchronicle.org/article/lucado-stepping-down-for-health-reasons Lucado stepping down for health reasons], ''Christian Chronicle'', May 2007, accessed March 3, 2014.</ref> Lucado has since resumed the more limited ministry role of writing and preaching at Oak Hills with co-pastor Randy Frazee, formerly of [[Willow Creek Community Church]] of [[South Barrington, Illinois]].\n\n==Opposition to homosexuality and gay rights==\n   \nCritics have described Lucado as having \"extreme views on gay rights\". Lucado has argued publicly that [[same-sex marriage]] will lead to bigamy, bestiality and incest. He raised concerns around \u2018legalized polygamy and other deviations\u2019 that will \u2018erode the traditional family\u2019 for example \"''A marriage between a daddy and a daughter or a woman and giraffe? Don\u2019t underestimate the evil bent of the human heart.''\n \n==Accomplishments==\nLucado has written almost 100 books <!-- at least 97 books --> with 130 million copies in print. He was recipient of the Charles \"Kip\" Jordon [[Gold Medallion Book Award|Gold Medallion Christian Book of the Year]] award three times for his books ''Just Like Jesus'', ''In the Grip of Grace'' and ''When God Whispers Your Name''),<ref>[http://www.ecpa.org/book_year.php Christian Book of the Year Past Winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403171803/http://www.ecpa.org/book_year.php |date=April 3, 2007 }}</ref> and has also appeared regularly on several bestseller lists including the [[New York Times Best Seller|''New York Times'' Best Seller List]].<ref name=christianbook/>\n\nLucado was named \"America's Pastor\" by ''[[Christianity Today]]'' magazine and in 2005 was named by ''Reader's Digest'' as \"The Best Preacher in America.\"<ref name=\"optimist05\">Tiffany Taylor [http://media.www.acuoptimist.com/media/storage/paper891/news/2005/04/29/News/readers.Digest.Honors.Alumnus-2430948.shtml \"'Reader's Digest' honors alumnus: Max Lucado named Best Preacher in America in magazine,\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928223104/http://media.www.acuoptimist.com/media/storage/paper891/news/2005/04/29/News/readers.Digest.Honors.Alumnus-2430948.shtml |date=September 28, 2007 }} ''The Optimist'' (Abilene Christian University), April 29, 2005</ref> He has also been featured on [[The Fox News Channel]], [[NBC Nightly News]], [[Larry King Live]], [[LLBN]], and [[USA Today]].  He has been a featured speaker at the [[National Prayer Breakfast]].{{fact|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Education==\n*B.A. [[Abilene Christian University]] (1977)<ref>{{cite web|last=Kilmer|first=Wendy|title=ACU to honor Max Lucado with top alumni award|url=http://www.acu.edu/events/news/archives2004/040211_Lucadoalumni.html|work=acu.edu|publisher=Abilene Christian University|accessdate=July 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529023633/http://www.acu.edu/events/news/archives2004/040211_Lucadoalumni.html|archive-date=May 29, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n*M.A. [[Abilene Christian University]]\n\n==Books==\n*''On the Anvil: Being Shaped into God's Image'', [[Carol Stream, Illinois]]: [[Tyndale House]], 1985. {{ISBN|978-1-4143-1553-9}}.\n*''No Wonder They Call Him the Savior'', [[New York, New York]]: [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday Publishing]], 1986. {{ISBN|978-0-8807-0611-7}}.\n*''God Came Near: Chronicles of the Christ'', [[Portland, Oregon]]: [[Random House|Multnomah Press]], 1987. {{ISBN|978-0-8807-0206-5}}.\n*''Six Hours One Friday: Anchoring to the Power of the Cross'' [[Portland, Oregon]]: [[Random House|Multnomah Press]], 1989. {{ISBN|978-0-8807-0314-7}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm1990.php|title=Christian Book Award\u00ae - ECPA|website=www.ecpa.org|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''The Applause of Heaven'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1990. {{ISBN|978-0-8499-1324-2}}.\n*''In the Eye of the Storm: A Day in the Life of Jesus'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1991. {{ISBN|978-0-8499-4325-6}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm1992.php|title=Christian Book Award\u00ae - ECPA|website=www.ecpa.org|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''Just In Case You Ever Wonder'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 1992.  P<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm1993.php|title=Christian Book Award\u00ae - ECPA|website=www.ecpa.org|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''And the Angels Were Silent'', [[Portland, Oregon]]: [[Random House|Multnomah Press]], 1992.\n*''Tell Me the Story'' [[Wheaton, Illinois]]: [[Good News Publishers|Crossway Books]], 1992.\n*''He Still Moves Stones'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1993.\n*''Tell Me the Secrets'', [[Wheaton, Illinois]]: [[Good News Publishers|Crossway Books]], 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm1994.php|title=Christian Book Award\u00ae - ECPA|website=www.ecpa.org|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''The Crippled Lamb'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 1994.<ref>[http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm1995.php 1995 Gold Medallion Book Awards Winners - Gift Book/Poetry] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518231031/http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm1995.php |date=May 18, 2008 }}</ref>\n*''When God Whispers Your Name'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1994.\n*''The Children of the King'', [[Wheaton, Illinois]]: [[Good News Publishers|Crossway Books]], 1994.\n*''The Final Week of Jesus'' [[Portland, Oregon]]: [[Random House|Multnomah Press]], 1994. {{ISBN|978-0-88070-630-8}}.\n*''A Gentle Thunder'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1995.\n*''The Song of the King'', [[Wheaton, Illinois]]: [[Good News Publishers|Crossway Books]], 1995.\n*''The Inspirational Study Bible'' [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 1995. {{ISBN|978-0-84995-123-7}}.\n*''In the Grip of Grace'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm1997.php|title=Christian Book Award\u00ae - ECPA|website=www.ecpa.org|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''The Glory of Christmas'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1996.\n*''God's Inspirational Promises'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1996.\n*''Walking with the Savior'', [[Carol Stream, Illinois]]: [[Tyndale House]], 1996.\n*''Alabaster's Song'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 1996.\n*''Life Lessons Bible Study Guides'' 1996-1998.\n*''[[The Great House of God]]'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1997.\n*''You Are Special'', [[Wheaton, Illinois]]: [[Good News Publishers|Crossway Books]], 1997.\n*''Cosmic Christmas: An Angel's Story'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1997.\n*''The Greatest Moments'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1997.\n*''The Cross'', [[Portland, Oregon]]: [[Random House|Multnomah Press]], 1998.\n*''The Heart of Christmas'', 1998.\n*''Just Like Jesus'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1998.\n*''The Christmas Cross'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1998. (the 2003 American Christian film, ''[[Christmas Child]]'', was based on this short story)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/christmas-child-max-lucado/1100330991|website=B&N.com Review |title=Christmas Child: A Story of Coming Home}}</ref>\n*''Let the Journey Begin'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1998.\n*''When Christ Comes'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 1999.\n*''Just the Way Your Are'', [[Wheaton, Illinois]]: [[Good News Publishers|Crossway Books]], 1999. \n*''The Gift for All People'', [[Portland, Oregon]]: [[Random House|Multnomah Press]], 1999.\n*''Opening Windows'', 1999.\n*''Because I Love You'', [[Wheaton, Illinois]]: [[Good News Publishers|Crossway Books]], 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm2000.php|title=Christian Book Award\u00ae - ECPA|website=www.ecpa.org|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''Topical Bible Study Series'', 1999-2000.\n*''He Chose the Nails'', [[Dallas, Texas]]: Word Publishing, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm2001.php|title=Christian Book Award\u00ae - ECPA|website=www.ecpa.org|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''[[Grace for the Moment]]'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|J. Countryman]], 2000.\n*''In the Footsteps of Jesus'', [[Carol Stream, Illinois]]: [[Tyndale House]], 2000.\n*''He Did This Just For You'', 2000.\n*''Small Gifts in God's Hands'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 2000.\n*''Traveling Light'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm2002.php|title=Christian Book Award\u00ae - ECPA|website=www.ecpa.org|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''Traveling Light Journal'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2001.\n*''America Looks Up'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2001.\n*''One Incredible Moment'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|J. Countryman]], 2001.\n*''Safe in the Shepherd's Arms'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|J. Countryman]], 2001.\n*''Just For You'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2002.\n*''A Love Worth Giving'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2002.\n*''Traveling Light for Mothers'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2002.\n*''He Chose You'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 2002.\n*''Just Like Jesus (Devotional)'', 2002.\n*''A Heart Like Jesus'', 2002.\n*''What the Cross Means to Me'', 2002.\n*''Next Door Savior'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm2004.php|title=Christian Book Award\u00ae - ECPA|website=www.ecpa.org|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''Experiencing the Heart of Jesus'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ecpa.org/christianbookawards/gm2004.php|title=Christian Book Award\u00ae - ECPA|website=www.ecpa.org|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''God Thinks You're Wonderful'', 2003. [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|J. Countryman]], 2003.\n*''[[Hermie and Friends|Hermie, A Common Caterpillar]]'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 2003. {{ISBN|1-4003-0126-2}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianbook.com/hermie-friends-board-books-common-caterpillar/max-lucado/9781400301263/pd/301262|title=Hermie and Friends Board Books, Hermie: A Common Caterpillar|publisher=|accessdate=April 2, 2018|via=www.christianbook.com}}</ref>\n*''It's Not About Me'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Integrity Publishers]], 2004.<ref>[http://www.ecpa.org/goldmedallion/gm2005.php 2005 Gold Medallion Book Awards Winners - Inspirational] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20071013142243/http://www.ecpa.org/goldmedallion/gm2005.php |date=October 13, 2007 }}</ref>\n*''Come Thirsty'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2004.\n*''Everyday Blessings'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|J. Countryman]], 2004.\n*''The Story: The Bible as One Continuing Story of God and His People\" [[Zondervan (publisher)|Zondervan]], 2005, 2008, 2011. Various editions, including Teen Edition {{ISBN|978-0-310-72280-9}}.\n*''Cure for the Common Life'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2005.\n*''Turn'', [[Portland, Oregon]]: [[Random House|Multnomah Press]], 2005.\n*''God\u2019s Mirror'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Integrity Publishers]], 2005.\n*''The Way Home: A Princess Story'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 2005.\n*''God\u2019s Promises For You'', 2006. (Updated Edition)\n*''Your Special Gift'', [[Wheaton, Illinois]]: [[Good News Publishers|Crossway Books]], 2006.\n*''Grace For The Moment II'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|J. Countryman]], 2006.\n*''Facing Your Giants'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2006.\n*''Every Day Deserves a Chance: Wake Up to the Gift of 24 Hours'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 2006.\n*''3:16: The Numbers of Hope'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|W Publishing Group]], 2007.\n*''Cast Of Characters'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 2008.\n*''Fearless'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 2009.\n*''You Changed My Life'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 2010.\n*''The Lucado Life Lessons Study Bible, NKJV'', 2010.\n*''Outlive Your Life: You Were Made to Make A Difference'', [[Nashville, Tennessee]]: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], 2010.\n*''Max on Life; Answers and Inspiration for Today's Questions'', 2011.\n*''God's Story, Your Story: When His Becomes Yours'', 2011. {{ISBN|0-310-29403-7}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianbook.com/gods-story-your-when-becomes-yours/max-lucado/9780310294030/pd/294031?product_redirect=1&Ntt=294031&item_code=&Ntk=keywords&event=ESRCP|title=God's Story, Your Story: When His Becomes Yours|publisher=|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''God's Story, Your Story: Youth Edition'', 2011. {{ISBN|0-310-72546-1}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianbook.com/gods-story-your-youth-edition/max-lucado/9780310725466/pd/725466?event=AAI|title=God's Story, Your Story: Youth Edition|publisher=|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref>\n*''The Christmas Candle'', [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)]], 2013.\n