{"title_page": "Rhyl", "text_new": "{{short description|Town in North Wales}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image_name = Rhyl Seafront - geograph.org.uk - 388762.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Rhyl seafront.\n|country = Wales\n|welsh_name = Y Rhyl\n|constituency_welsh_assembly = [[Vale of Clwyd (Assembly constituency)|Vale of Clwyd]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Vale of Clwyd (UK Parliament constituency)|Vale of Clwyd]]\n|official_name = Rhyl\n|population = 25,149\n|population_ref = ''(2011)''\n|community_wales = Rhyl\n|unitary_wales = [[Denbighshire]]\n|lieutenancy_wales = [[Clwyd]]\n|post_town = RHYL\n|postcode_district = LL18\n|postcode_area = LL\n|dial_code = 01745\n|os_grid_reference = SJ015815\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.321|-3.480|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Rhyl''' ({{IPAc-en|r|\u026a|l}}; {{lang-cy|Y Rhyl}}, {{IPA-cy|\u0259 \u02c8r\u0325\u0268l|pron}}) is a [[seaside resort]] and [[community (Wales)|community]] in the [[Local government in Wales|Welsh county]] of [[Denbighshire]]. It lies within the [[Historic counties of Wales|historic boundaries]] of [[Flintshire (historic)|Flintshire]], on the north-east coast of [[Wales]] at the mouth of the [[River Clwyd]] ([[Welsh language|Welsh:]] ''Afon Clwyd''). To the west is the suburb of [[Kinmel Bay]] and the resort of [[Towyn]] beyond, to the east [[Prestatyn]], and to the south [[Rhuddlan]]. At the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]], Rhyl had a population of 25,149, with Rhyl-Kinmel Bay having 31,229.<ref>{{NOMIS2011 |id=1170221471 |title=Rhyl Parish |accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> The Abergele\u2013Rhyl\u2013Prestatyn conurbation numbers over 60,000. Once an elegant [[Victorian era|Victorian]] resort, an influx from [[Liverpool]] and [[Manchester]] after the [[Second World War]] changed the town's face. It had declined sharply by 1990, but has since been improved by major regeneration investments. Several million pounds of [[European Union]] funding secured by the [[Welsh Government]] has been spent on developing the seafront.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe origin of the name \"Rhyl\" is not fully known. It appears in old documents variously as ''Hulle'' (1292), ''Hul'' (1296), ''Ryhull'' (1301), ''Hyll'' (1506), ''Hull'' (1508), [Leidiart] ''yr Hyll'' (1597), ''Rhil'' (1706), ''Rh\u00fbl'' (1749), ''Rhul'' (1773) ''Rhyll'' (1830), and ''Rhyl'' (1840).<ref name=Dictionary>{{Cite book |title=Dictionary of the Place-Names of Wales |last2=Morgan |first2=Richard |year=2007 |publisher= |isbn=978-1-84323-901-7 |page=422 |last1=Owen |first1=Hywel Wyn}}</ref> The name seems to be a hybrid of the English word \"hill\" and the Welsh definite article \"y\". Its exact significance is unclear as there are no hills in the vicinity. It may refer to a mound or raised place in an otherwise marshy region. Some documents refer to a dwelling house, ''T\u0177'n yr haul'', meaning \"House in the sun\".<ref name=Dictionary/>\n\n==Buildings and landmarks==\n[[File:Rhyl East Parade clock tower.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.25|Rhyl clock tower and East Parade]]\n[[File:Rhyl, Denbighshire, Wales - Part 2 with view over town, prom, sun centre and beach.webm|thumb|upright=1.25|A short video of the beach with Sun centre, 2019]]\n\nRhyl has a number of Grade II [[listed building]]s and landmarks. These include the Parish Church of St Thomas in Bath Street, which is listed as Grade II*, a fine example of high Victorian Gothic and a prominent feature on the town landscape.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-1422-parish-church-of-st-thomas-rhyl#.VyRK7eTGA4A |title=Parish Church of St Thomas, Rhyl |publisher=British Listed Buildings |accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref> Others are the [[Midland Bank]] building, the railway station along with two signal boxes and the public telephone box on the up platform, the [[Royal Alexandra Hospital, Rhyl|Royal Alexandra Hospital]], the Sussex Street [[Baptist Church]]; the Town Hall; the ''Swan'' public house in Russell Road, the [[war memorial]], and the [[Presbyterian Church of Wales|Welsh Presbyterian Church]] in Clwyd Street.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wales/denbighshire/rhyl#.VyRLf-TGA4B |title=Listed Buildings in Rhyl, Wales |publisher=British Listed Buildings |accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:David Cox - Rhyl Sands (Tate version).jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.95|[[David Cox (artist)|David Cox]], ''Rhyl Sands'' (c.1854), depicting the Rhyl seafront]] Also notable is the Grade II listed Foryd Harbour Bridge, a blue bridge with distinctive bowstring girders, built in 1932. It links Rhyl with Kinmel Bay.\n\nAnother landmark is the Church of [[Margaret the Virgin|St Margaret of Antioch]]. The Marble Church was built by Lady Margaret in memory of her late husband, Sir Henry Peyto Willoughby de Broke. Within four years the church was completed, and it was consecrated on 23 August 1860, becoming the parish church of a newly formed Parish of Bodelwyddan, covering an area formerly part of the Parish of [[St Asaph]]. The church is open daily from 9:30 to 16:30 throughout the year, except between 25 December and 6 January. Access is via a gently-sloping ramp at the west door. St Margaret's is one of Britain's finest Victorian churches, with an interior decorated with a variety of marble.\n\nA previous Rhyl landmark was the Pavilion Theatre, an ornate building with five domes, which was demolished in 1974. Beside it stood the pier which was built in 1872 for the pleasure of the many visitors who flocked to the North Wales coast. It was {{convert|2355|ft|0}} long and once included a pier railway. The structure was damaged by ships in 1883 and again in 1891. It was also damaged in 1901 when there was a fire at the Pavilion Theatre. Storms were responsible for further damage in 1909 and the pier was closed in 1913 as unsafe. It was reopened with a much-reduced length in 1930 but closed again in 1966, before being demolished in 1972.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.piers.org.uk/pierpages/NPSrhyl.html |title=History of Rhyl Pier |publisher=National Piers Society |accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nRhyl's top attractions on the West Parade are Rhyl Children's Village theme park, and the {{convert|250|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} Sky Tower (formerly the [[Clydesdale Bank]] tower, brought to Rhyl from the 1988 [[Glasgow Garden Festival]]). The skytower opened in 1989,<ref>{{Cite book |title=Tourism in Peripheral Areas: Case Studies |url=http://www.bookdepository.com/book/9781873150238 |year=2000 |publisher=Channel View Publications Ltd |isbn=978-1-8731502-3-8 |page=31}}</ref> but was closed to the public in 2010. It was transformed into a light beacon in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/work-turn-rhyl-sky-tower-12715751 |title=Work to turn Rhyl Sky Tower into 'landmark' light beacon begins |work=Daily Post |date=11 March 2017 |accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rhyljournal.co.uk/news/111913/skytower-stays-shut-iconic-landmark-still-grounded.aspx |title=Sky Tower stays shut |work=Rhyl Journal |date=11 April 2012 |accessdate=28 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-east-wales-19567425 |title=Rhyl Skytower may still have a future but not as a ride |work=BBC News |date=12 September 2012 |accessdate=28 November 2013}}</ref> A [[Vue Cinemas|VUE Cinema]] is also located there.\n\nOn the East Parade is the SeaQuarium. Up until 2014, Rhyl Suncentre was also an attraction on the East Parade; an indoor water leisure centre which opened in 1980 at a cost of \u00a34.25 million and featured a heated swimming pool, water chutes and slides, and Europe's first indoor surfing pool.<ref>{{Cite news |title=The Sun Centre, Rhyl |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/domesday/dblock/GB-300000-381000/page/5 |newspaper=BBC: Domesday Reloaded |year=1989 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> The local council closed the centre in early 2014 and it was demolished in 2016. A new [[Travelodge]] hotel was built next to the site, which opened in early 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rhyl Sun Centre will not re-open as \"wet attraction\" |author=|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-east-wales-26736460 |newspaper=BBC News|date=25 March 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> Also on the East Parade is the Pavilion Theatre, opened in 1991. It has over 1,000 seats and is managed by Denbighshire County Council.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rhylpavilion.co.uk/ |title=Pavilion Theatre, Rhyl |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Marine Lake===\nThe Marine Lake, an artificial excavation in the west of the town, used to be a tourist destination, with fairground rides and a zoo. The lake is a 12-hectare man-made reservoir and it was officially opened in 1895. [[Rhyl Miniature Railway]] is the only original attraction remaining on the site, a [[narrow gauge]] railway that travels around the lake and is now based at the new museum and railway centre. There is also a playground and numerous watersports clubs based around the lake.<ref>{{Cite book |author=Howe, Marjorie |title=Old Rhyl: From 1850s \u2013 1910 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lxvp6HyZuhMC&pg=PA60 |year=2000  |publisher=Gwasg Helygain Ltd |isbn=978-0-9522755-4-1 |page=60}}</ref>\n[[File:Ocean beach fun fair site rhyl dec 2007.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.95|Former [[Ocean Beach, Rhyl|Ocean Beach Funfair]] site (December 2007)]]\nThe Marine Lake Funfair was demolished in the late 1960s, having been replaced by the nearby [[Ocean Beach, Rhyl|Ocean Beach Funfair]]. Ocean Beach finally closed on 2 September 2007 and was demolished to make way for a planned new development initially called Ocean Plaza. This was to include apartments, a hotel and various retail outlets.<ref name=BBCfair>{{Cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/north_east/6968961.stm |title=End of an era for Rhyl's funfair |work=BBC News |date=2 September 2007 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> However, work on Ocean Plaza never went ahead as scheduled and the land lay vacant for several years after the original developers, Modus Properties, went bankrupt in 2009. The site was sold to a new company, Scarborough Development Group (SDG), in 2010, but again no work commenced on the site for several years. In 2014, SDG submitted revised plans to develop the land on a much smaller scale than the original plans.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Plans for Ocean Plaza development go on display |url=http://www.newsnorthwales.co.uk/news/130824/plans-for-ocean-plaza-development-go-on-display.aspx |newspaper=News North Wales |date=7 February 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> Now called Marina Quay, the plans no longer include the building of new apartments on the land as [[Natural Resources Wales]]' flood regulations now prohibit this.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rhyl Ocean Plaza: Backlash over downsized plans for derelict funfair |author=Williams, Kelly |url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/rhyl-ocean-plaza-backlash-over-6677086 |newspaper=Daily Post |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> The plans were approved by the local authority in November 2014. In August 2015, [[The Range (retailer)|The Range]] retail chain signed a 20-year lease and opened a new superstore on the site in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rhyl funfair site secures The Range as anchor tenant |author=Hughes, Owen |url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/business/business-news/rhyl-ocean-plaza-funfair-range-9790961 |newspaper=Daily Post |date=4 August 2015 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Regeneration project===\nIn an effort to regenerate and boost declining tourism, a number of projects are under way or proposed. Projects include the Drift Park development on the promenade and the reopening of the town's miniature railway around the Marine Lake. The West End of Rhyl is undergoing much reconstruction. There is a major investment of about \u00a34 million at Rhyl College, a satellite site of [[Llandrillo College]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.llandrillo.ac.uk/rhyl/rhylrevamp.htm |title=\u00a34m for Rhyl Creates New Opportunities and Jobs |work=Coleg Llandrillo Rhyl |accessdate=16 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080107021718/http://www.llandrillo.ac.uk/rhyl/rhylrevamp.htm |archivedate= 7 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=POLL: Ambitious plans for Rhyl seafront regeneration unveiled |author= |url=http://rhyljournal.co.uk/news/155625/poll-ambitious-plans-for-rhyl-seafront-regeneration-unveiled.aspx |newspaper=Rhyl, Prestatyn & Abergele Journal |date=2 December 2015 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Electoral wards in the town of Rhyl, Denbighshire, Wales.png|thumb|250px|Electoral wards in and surrounding Rhyl (county=pink; town=grey)]]\nFor elections to [[Denbighshire County Council]], Rhyl is divided into five [[electoral ward]]s: Rhyl East, Rhyl South, Rhyl South East, Rhyl South West and [[Rhyl West]]. Following the 2017 elections all except two of the eleven councillors represented the [[Welsh Labour]] Party.<ref>Gareth Joy (5 May 2017) [http://www.pointfm.co.uk/election-2017-denbighshire-council-results/ Election 2017: Denbighshire Council results], ''[[Point FM]]''. Retrieved 30 March 2018.</ref> In 2008 Rhyl West was measured as the most deprived ward in Wales, according to the Welsh Index of Multiple Deprivation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/7661824.stm |title=MP paints out town's tainted past |work=BBC News |date=10 October 2008 |accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor election of the 22 town councillors to [[Rhyl Town Council]], the town is divided into nine community wards: Brynhedydd and Plastirion (in Rhyl East); Cefndy, Derwen, Pendyffryn, Trellewellyn and Tynewydd (Rhyl South, South East and South West); Bodfor and Foryd (in Rhyl West).<ref>[http://rhyltowncouncil.org.uk/councillors.html Councillors], Rhyl Town Council website. Retrieved 30 March 2018.</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n'''Association Football'''\n[[Rhyl F.C.]], commonly known as the Lilywhites, is a football club which historically played in English non-league football, but has competed since 1992 in the [[Welsh football pyramid]]. In the 2003\u20132004 season it won the [[League of Wales|Welsh Premier League]], the [[Welsh Cup]] and the Welsh League Cup, and was losing finalist in the [[UEFA Champions League|FAW]] Premier Cup. In the 2008\u20132009 season it again won the Welsh Premier League.<ref name=Lilywhites>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rhylfc.co.uk/clubinfo/club-history |title=Club history |publisher=Rhyl F.C. |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> On 17 May 2010, it was announced that Rhyl's Welsh Premier licence had been revoked. Its appeal was unsuccessful and they were relegated to the Cymru Alliance,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rhyl FC's Welsh Premier appeal fails FAW test |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_of_wales/8688196.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> returning to the [[Welsh Premier League]] in 2013 after winning the Cymru Alliance title, becoming the first club in the history of the competition to complete the season unbeaten.<ref name=Lilywhites/> Rhyl has played in Europe on a few occasions.\n\n'''Rugby Union'''\nRhyl and District RFC is the town's rugby union club, but had never had a playing base in the town until this year, when a new ground and clubhouse opened.\n\n'''Hockey'''\nRhyl is home to the oldest field hockey club in Wales, formed in 1890. Its first international game was also played at Rhyl, between Ireland and Wales in 1895.\n\n==Climate==\nThe climate is cool and temperate in Rhyl. The climate here is classified as Cfb by the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]. The average temperature in Rhyl is {{Convert|9.3|C}}. Annual precipitation averages 794 mm.\n\n==Transport==\n[[Rhyl railway station]] is on the [[North Wales Coast Line]] and is served by through trains of [[Avanti West Coast]] between [[Holyhead railway station|Holyhead]] and [[Euston railway station|London Euston]], and [[Transport for Wales Rail Services|Transport for Wales]] services to [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff Central]] via [[Newport railway station|Newport]] and [[Crewe railway station|Crewe]], and to [[Manchester Piccadilly station|Manchester Piccadilly]]. Other nearby stations include [[Abergele & Pensarn railway station|Abergele & Pensarn]], [[Prestatyn railway station|Prestatyn]], [[Flint railway station|Flint]], [[Colwyn Bay railway station|Colwyn Bay]] and [[Llandudno Junction railway station|Llandudno Junction]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nwrail.org.uk/nwroute1.htm |title=Crewe to Holyhead |year=2012 |publisher=North Wales Coast Railway |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> Rhyl has direct Transport for Wales and Avanti West Coast services to Holyhead, which give connections by [[Stena Line]] or [[Irish Ferries]] to [[Port of Dublin|Dublin Port]].\n\nThe [[A548 road]] through the town connects it to the [[A55 road|A55]] Holyhead to [[Chester]] road at [[Abergele]]. The [[A525 road]] runs south from the town to [[Rhuddlan]], [[St Asaph]] and [[Ruthin]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=Concise Road Atlas: Britain |year=2015 |publisher=AA Publishing |isbn=978-0-7495-7743-8 |pages=47\u201355 }}</ref> Several bus services are run by [[Arriva Buses Wales]] along the main coast road between Chester and Holyhead, linking the coastal resorts. Another route runs between Rhyl and Denbigh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arrivabus.co.uk/wales/ |title=Discover the towns of Wales |work=Arriva Wales |publisher=Arriva Buses Wales |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\nIn alphabetical order:\n*[[Thomas Aubrey (Methodist minister)|Thomas Aubrey]] (1808\u20131867), minister and travelling preacher\n*[[Wayne Bickerton]] (1941\u20132015), record producer and musician\n*[[James Chester]] (born 1989), international footballer ([[Aston Villa F.C.]])\n*[[Alexa Davies]] (born 1995), actress best known for Young Rosie in ''[[Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again]]''\n*[[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]] (born 1964), comedian and actor\n*[[Ruth Ellis]] (1926\u20131955), nightclub hostess and murderer, last woman to be hanged in England\n*[[Ched Evans]] (born 1988), footballer ([[Sheffield United F.C.]])\n*[[Elliott Hewitt]] (born 1944), professional footballer ([[Notts County F.C.]])\n*[[Nerys Hughes]] (born 1941), actress\n*[[Isaac Jenks]] (1816\u20131888), ironmaster and [[Mayor of Wolverhampton]], who died at Rhyl\n*[[Ann Jones (politician)|Ann Jones]] (born 1953), [[Welsh Labour]] and [[Co-operative Party]] MP\n*[[Mungo Lewis]] (1894\u20131969), [[Manitoba]] politician\n*[[Don Oakes (footballer)|Don Oakes]] (1928\u20131977), professional footballer ([[Arsenal F.C.]])\n*[[Nathan Penlington]] (living), writer, poet and magician\n*[[Mike Peters (musician)|Michael Leslie Peters]] (born 1959), lead singer and founding member of the group ''[[The Alarm]]'', born in [[Prestatyn]], grew up in Rhyl, attending Rhyl High School.\n*[[William Roberts (footballer, born 1863)|William Roberts]] (born 1863, fl. 1880s \u2013 1890s), international footballer\n*[[Lisa Scott-Lee]] (born 1975), singer and dancer\n*[[Steve Strange]] (1959\u20132015), pop musician\n*[[Sara Sugarman]] (born 1962), actress and film director\n*[[Carol Vorderman]] (born 1960), TV broadcaster and game-show host, attended Rhyl's Blessed Edward Jones High School\n*[[Edward Ross Wharton]] (1844\u20131896), classical scholar, etymologist and lexicographer<ref>Bibliography backing description: [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/webbin/book/lookupname?key=Wharton%2C%20Edward%20Ross%2C%201844-1896 Retrieved 7 February 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Spencer Wilding]] (born 1972), actor best known for Darth Vader in ''[[Rogue One]]''\n*[[Vernon R. Young]] (1937\u20132004), research scientist specializing in [[protein]] and [[amino acid]] requirements\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rhyl}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Rhyl}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northeast/sites/rhyl_town/ BBC Rhyl page]\n*[http://rhyltowncouncil.org.uk/ Rhyl town council page]\n\n{{Denbighshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rhyl| ]]\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in Wales]]\n[[Category:Towns in Denbighshire]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Town in North Wales}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image_name = Rhyl Seafront - geograph.org.uk - 388762.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Rhyl seafront.\n|country = Wales\n|welsh_name = Y Rhyl\n|constituency_welsh_assembly = [[Vale of Clwyd (Assembly constituency)|Vale of Clwyd]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Vale of Clwyd (UK Parliament constituency)|Vale of Clwyd]]\n|official_name = Rhyl\n|population = 25,149\n|population_ref = ''(2011)''\n|community_wales = Rhyl\n|unitary_wales = [[Denbighshire]]\n|lieutenancy_wales = [[Clwyd]]\n|post_town = RHYL\n|postcode_district = LL18\n|postcode_area = LL\n|dial_code = 01745\n|os_grid_reference = SJ015815\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.321|-3.480|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Rhyl''' ({{IPAc-en|r|\u026a|l}}; {{lang-cy|Y Rhyl}}, {{IPA-cy|\u0259 \u02c8r\u0325\u0268l|pron}}) is a [[seaside resort]] and [[community (Wales)|community]] in the [[Local government in Wales|Welsh county]] of [[Denbighshire]]. It lies within the [[Historic counties of Wales|historic boundaries]] of [[Flintshire (historic)|Flintshire]], on the north-east coast of [[Wales]] at the mouth of the [[River Clwyd]] ([[Welsh language|Welsh:]] ''Afon Clwyd''). To the west is the suburb of [[Kinmel Bay]] and the resort of [[Towyn]] beyond, to the east [[Prestatyn]], and to the south [[Rhuddlan]]. At the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]], Rhyl had a population of 25,149, with Rhyl-Kinmel Bay having 31,229.<ref>{{NOMIS2011 |id=1170221471 |title=Rhyl Parish |accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> The Abergele\u2013Rhyl\u2013Prestatyn conurbation numbers over 60,000. Once an elegant [[Victorian era|Victorian]] resort, an influx from [[Liverpool]] and [[Manchester]] after the [[Second World War]] changed the town's face=. It had declined dramatically by 1990, but has since been improved by regeneration projects with major investment. Several million pounds of [[European Union]] funding secured by the [[Welsh Government]] has been spent on developing the seafront.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe origin of the name \"Rhyl\" is not fully known. It appears in old documents variously as ''Hulle'' (1292), ''Hul'' (1296), ''Ryhull'' (1301), ''Hyll'' (1506), ''Hull'' (1508), [Leidiart] ''yr Hyll'' (1597), ''Rhil'' (1706), ''Rh\u00fbl'' (1749), ''Rhul'' (1773) ''Rhyll'' (1830), and ''Rhyl'' (1840).<ref name=Dictionary>{{Cite book |title=Dictionary of the Place-Names of Wales |last2=Morgan |first2=Richard |year=2007 |publisher= |isbn=978-1-84323-901-7 |page=422 |last1=Owen |first1=Hywel Wyn}}</ref> The name seems to be a hybrid of the English word \"hill\" and the Welsh definite article \"y\". Its exact significance is unclear as there are no hills in the vicinity. It may refer to a mound or raised place in an otherwise marshy region. Some documents refer to a dwelling house, ''T\u0177'n yr haul'', meaning \"House in the sun\".<ref name=Dictionary/>\n\n==Buildings and landmarks==\n[[File:Rhyl East Parade clock tower.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.25|Rhyl clock tower and East Parade]]\n[[File:Rhyl, Denbighshire, Wales - Part 2 with view over town, prom, sun centre and beach.webm|thumb|upright=1.25|A short video of the beach with Sun centre, 2019]]\n\nRhyl has a number of Grade II [[listed building]]s and landmarks. These include the Parish Church of St Thomas in Bath Street, which is listed as Grade II*, a fine example of high Victorian Gothic and a prominent feature on the town landscape.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-1422-parish-church-of-st-thomas-rhyl#.VyRK7eTGA4A |title=Parish Church of St Thomas, Rhyl |publisher=British Listed Buildings |accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref> Others are the [[Midland Bank]] building, the railway station along with two signal boxes and the public telephone box on the up platform, the [[Royal Alexandra Hospital, Rhyl|Royal Alexandra Hospital]], the Sussex Street [[Baptist Church]]; the Town Hall; the ''Swan'' public house in Russell Road, the [[war memorial]], and the [[Presbyterian Church of Wales|Welsh Presbyterian Church]] in Clwyd Street.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wales/denbighshire/rhyl#.VyRLf-TGA4B |title=Listed Buildings in Rhyl, Wales |publisher=British Listed Buildings |accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:David Cox - Rhyl Sands (Tate version).jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.95|[[David Cox (artist)|David Cox]], ''Rhyl Sands'' (c.1854), depicting the Rhyl seafront]] Also notable is the Grade II listed Foryd Harbour Bridge, a blue bridge with distinctive bowstring girders, built in 1932. It links Rhyl with Kinmel Bay.\n\nAnother landmark is the Church of [[Margaret the Virgin|St Margaret of Antioch]]. The Marble Church was built by Lady Margaret in memory of her late husband, Sir Henry Peyto Willoughby de Broke. Within four years the church was completed, and it was consecrated on 23 August 1860, becoming the parish church of a newly formed Parish of Bodelwyddan, covering an area formerly part of the Parish of [[St Asaph]]. The church is open daily from 9:30 to 16:30 throughout the year, except between 25 December and 6 January. Access is via a gently-sloping ramp at the west door. St Margaret's is one of Britain's finest Victorian churches, with an interior decorated with a variety of marble.\n\nA previous Rhyl landmark was the Pavilion Theatre, an ornate building with five domes, which was demolished in 1974. Beside it stood the pier which was built in 1872 for the pleasure of the many visitors who flocked to the North Wales coast. It was {{convert|2355|ft|0}} long and once included a pier railway. The structure was damaged by ships in 1883 and again in 1891. It was also damaged in 1901 when there was a fire at the Pavilion Theatre. Storms were responsible for further damage in 1909 and the pier was closed in 1913 as unsafe. It was reopened with a much-reduced length in 1930 but closed again in 1966, before being demolished in 1972.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.piers.org.uk/pierpages/NPSrhyl.html |title=History of Rhyl Pier |publisher=National Piers Society |accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nRhyl's top attractions on the West Parade are Rhyl Children's Village theme park, and the {{convert|250|ft|m|adj=mid|-high}} Sky Tower (formerly the [[Clydesdale Bank]] tower, brought to Rhyl from the 1988 [[Glasgow Garden Festival]]). The skytower opened in 1989,<ref>{{Cite book |title=Tourism in Peripheral Areas: Case Studies |url=http://www.bookdepository.com/book/9781873150238 |year=2000 |publisher=Channel View Publications Ltd |isbn=978-1-8731502-3-8 |page=31}}</ref> but was closed to the public in 2010. It was transformed into a light beacon in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/work-turn-rhyl-sky-tower-12715751 |title=Work to turn Rhyl Sky Tower into 'landmark' light beacon begins |work=Daily Post |date=11 March 2017 |accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rhyljournal.co.uk/news/111913/skytower-stays-shut-iconic-landmark-still-grounded.aspx |title=Sky Tower stays shut |work=Rhyl Journal |date=11 April 2012 |accessdate=28 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-east-wales-19567425 |title=Rhyl Skytower may still have a future but not as a ride |work=BBC News |date=12 September 2012 |accessdate=28 November 2013}}</ref> A [[Vue Cinemas|VUE Cinema]] is also located there.\n\nOn the East Parade is the SeaQuarium. Up until 2014, Rhyl Suncentre was also an attraction on the East Parade; an indoor water leisure centre which opened in 1980 at a cost of \u00a34.25 million and featured a heated swimming pool, water chutes and slides, and Europe's first indoor surfing pool.<ref>{{Cite news |title=The Sun Centre, Rhyl |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/domesday/dblock/GB-300000-381000/page/5 |newspaper=BBC: Domesday Reloaded |year=1989 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> The local council closed the centre in early 2014 and it was demolished in 2016. A new [[Travelodge]] hotel was built next to the site, which opened in early 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rhyl Sun Centre will not re-open as \"wet attraction\" |author=|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-east-wales-26736460 |newspaper=BBC News|date=25 March 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> Also on the East Parade is the Pavilion Theatre, opened in 1991. It has over 1,000 seats and is managed by Denbighshire County Council.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rhylpavilion.co.uk/ |title=Pavilion Theatre, Rhyl |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Marine Lake===\nThe Marine Lake, an artificial excavation in the west of the town, used to be a tourist destination, with fairground rides and a zoo. The lake is a 12-hectare man-made reservoir and it was officially opened in 1895. [[Rhyl Miniature Railway]] is the only original attraction remaining on the site, a [[narrow gauge]] railway that travels around the lake and is now based at the new museum and railway centre. There is also a playground and numerous watersports clubs based around the lake.<ref>{{Cite book |author=Howe, Marjorie |title=Old Rhyl: From 1850s \u2013 1910 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lxvp6HyZuhMC&pg=PA60 |year=2000  |publisher=Gwasg Helygain Ltd |isbn=978-0-9522755-4-1 |page=60}}</ref>\n[[File:Ocean beach fun fair site rhyl dec 2007.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.95|Former [[Ocean Beach, Rhyl|Ocean Beach Funfair]] site (December 2007)]]\nThe Marine Lake Funfair was demolished in the late 1960s, having been replaced by the nearby [[Ocean Beach, Rhyl|Ocean Beach Funfair]]. Ocean Beach finally closed on 2 September 2007 and was demolished to make way for a planned new development initially called Ocean Plaza. This was to include apartments, a hotel and various retail outlets.<ref name=BBCfair>{{Cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/north_east/6968961.stm |title=End of an era for Rhyl's funfair |work=BBC News |date=2 September 2007 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> However, work on Ocean Plaza never went ahead as scheduled and the land lay vacant for several years after the original developers, Modus Properties, went bankrupt in 2009. The site was sold to a new company, Scarborough Development Group (SDG), in 2010, but again no work commenced on the site for several years. In 2014, SDG submitted revised plans to develop the land on a much smaller scale than the original plans.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Plans for Ocean Plaza development go on display |url=http://www.newsnorthwales.co.uk/news/130824/plans-for-ocean-plaza-development-go-on-display.aspx |newspaper=News North Wales |date=7 February 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> Now called Marina Quay, the plans no longer include the building of new apartments on the land as [[Natural Resources Wales]]' flood regulations now prohibit this.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rhyl Ocean Plaza: Backlash over downsized plans for derelict funfair |author=Williams, Kelly |url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/rhyl-ocean-plaza-backlash-over-6677086 |newspaper=Daily Post |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> The plans were approved by the local authority in November 2014. In August 2015, [[The Range (retailer)|The Range]] retail chain signed a 20-year lease and opened a new superstore on the site in March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rhyl funfair site secures The Range as anchor tenant |author=Hughes, Owen |url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/business/business-news/rhyl-ocean-plaza-funfair-range-9790961 |newspaper=Daily Post |date=4 August 2015 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Regeneration project===\nIn an effort to regenerate and boost declining tourism, a number of projects are under way or proposed. Projects include the Drift Park development on the promenade and the reopening of the town's miniature railway around the Marine Lake. The West End of Rhyl is undergoing much reconstruction. There is a major investment of about \u00a34 million at Rhyl College, a satellite site of [[Llandrillo College]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.llandrillo.ac.uk/rhyl/rhylrevamp.htm |title=\u00a34m for Rhyl Creates New Opportunities and Jobs |work=Coleg Llandrillo Rhyl |accessdate=16 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080107021718/http://www.llandrillo.ac.uk/rhyl/rhylrevamp.htm |archivedate= 7 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=POLL: Ambitious plans for Rhyl seafront regeneration unveiled |author= |url=http://rhyljournal.co.uk/news/155625/poll-ambitious-plans-for-rhyl-seafront-regeneration-unveiled.aspx |newspaper=Rhyl, Prestatyn & Abergele Journal |date=2 December 2015 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Electoral wards in the town of Rhyl, Denbighshire, Wales.png|thumb|250px|Electoral wards in and surrounding Rhyl (county=pink; town=grey)]]\nFor elections to [[Denbighshire County Council]], Rhyl is divided into five [[electoral ward]]s: Rhyl East, Rhyl South, Rhyl South East, Rhyl South West and [[Rhyl West]]. Following the 2017 elections all except two of the eleven councillors represented the [[Welsh Labour]] Party.<ref>Gareth Joy (5 May 2017) [http://www.pointfm.co.uk/election-2017-denbighshire-council-results/ Election 2017: Denbighshire Council results], ''[[Point FM]]''. Retrieved 30 March 2018.</ref> In 2008 Rhyl West was measured as the most deprived ward in Wales, according to the Welsh Index of Multiple Deprivation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/7661824.stm |title=MP paints out town's tainted past |work=BBC News |date=10 October 2008 |accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor election of the 22 town councillors to [[Rhyl Town Council]], the town is divided into nine community wards: Brynhedydd and Plastirion (in Rhyl East); Cefndy, Derwen, Pendyffryn, Trellewellyn and Tynewydd (Rhyl South, South East and South West); Bodfor and Foryd (in Rhyl West).<ref>[http://rhyltowncouncil.org.uk/councillors.html Councillors], Rhyl Town Council website. Retrieved 30 March 2018.</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n'''Association Football'''\n[[Rhyl F.C.]], commonly known as the Lilywhites, is a football club which historically played in English non-league football, but has competed since 1992 in the [[Welsh football pyramid]]. In the 2003\u20132004 season it won the [[League of Wales|Welsh Premier League]], the [[Welsh Cup]] and the Welsh League Cup, and was losing finalist in the [[UEFA Champions League|FAW]] Premier Cup. In the 2008\u20132009 season it again won the Welsh Premier League.<ref name=Lilywhites>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rhylfc.co.uk/clubinfo/club-history |title=Club history |publisher=Rhyl F.C. |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> On 17 May 2010, it was announced that Rhyl's Welsh Premier licence had been revoked. Its appeal was unsuccessful and they were relegated to the Cymru Alliance,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Rhyl FC's Welsh Premier appeal fails FAW test |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_of_wales/8688196.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> returning to the [[Welsh Premier League]] in 2013 after winning the Cymru Alliance title, becoming the first club in the history of the competition to complete the season unbeaten.<ref name=Lilywhites/> Rhyl has played in Europe on a few occasions.\n\n'''Rugby Union'''\nRhyl and District RFC is the town's rugby union club, but had never had a playing base in the town until this year, when a new ground and clubhouse opened.\n\n'''Hockey'''\nRhyl is home to the oldest field hockey club in Wales, formed in 1890. Its first international game was also played at Rhyl, between Ireland and Wales in 1895.\n\n==Climate==\nThe climate is cool and temperate in Rhyl. The climate here is classified as Cfb by the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]. The average temperature in Rhyl is {{Convert|9.3|C}}. Annual precipitation averages 794 mm.\n\n==Transport==\n[[Rhyl railway station]] is on the [[North Wales Coast Line]] and is served by through trains of [[Avanti West Coast]] between [[Holyhead railway station|Holyhead]] and [[Euston railway station|London Euston]], and [[Transport for Wales Rail Services|Transport for Wales]] services to [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff Central]] via [[Newport railway station|Newport]] and [[Crewe railway station|Crewe]], and to [[Manchester Piccadilly station|Manchester Piccadilly]]. Other nearby stations include [[Abergele & Pensarn railway station|Abergele & Pensarn]], [[Prestatyn railway station|Prestatyn]], [[Flint railway station|Flint]], [[Colwyn Bay railway station|Colwyn Bay]] and [[Llandudno Junction railway station|Llandudno Junction]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nwrail.org.uk/nwroute1.htm |title=Crewe to Holyhead |year=2012 |publisher=North Wales Coast Railway |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> Rhyl has direct Transport for Wales and Avanti West Coast services to Holyhead, which give connections by [[Stena Line]] or [[Irish Ferries]] to [[Port of Dublin|Dublin Port]].\n\nThe [[A548 road]] through the town connects it to the [[A55 road|A55]] Holyhead to [[Chester]] road at [[Abergele]]. The [[A525 road]] runs south from the town to [[Rhuddlan]], [[St Asaph]] and [[Ruthin]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=Concise Road Atlas: Britain |year=2015 |publisher=AA Publishing |isbn=978-0-7495-7743-8 |pages=47\u201355 }}</ref> Several bus services are run by [[Arriva Buses Wales]] along the main coast road between Chester and Holyhead, linking the coastal resorts. Another route runs between Rhyl and Denbigh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arrivabus.co.uk/wales/ |title=Discover the towns of Wales |work=Arriva Wales |publisher=Arriva Buses Wales |accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\nIn alphabetical order:\n*[[Thomas Aubrey (Methodist minister)|Thomas Aubrey]] (1808\u20131867), minister and travelling preacher\n*[[Wayne Bickerton]] (1941\u20132015), record producer and musician\n*[[James Chester]] (born 1989), international footballer ([[Aston Villa F.C.]])\n*[[Alexa Davies]] (born 1995), actress best known for Young Rosie in ''[[Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again]]''\n*[[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]] (born 1964), comedian and actor\n*[[Ruth Ellis]] (1926\u20131955), nightclub hostess and murderer, last woman to be hanged in England\n*[[Ched Evans]] (born 1988), footballer ([[Sheffield United F.C.]])\n*[[Elliott Hewitt]] (born 1944), professional footballer ([[Notts County F.C.]])\n*[[Nerys Hughes]] (born 1941), actress\n*[[Isaac Jenks]] (1816\u20131888), ironmaster and [[Mayor of Wolverhampton]], who died at Rhyl\n*[[Ann Jones (politician)|Ann Jones]] (born 1953), [[Welsh Labour]] and [[Co-operative Party]] MP\n*[[Mungo Lewis]] (1894\u20131969), [[Manitoba]] politician\n*[[Don Oakes (footballer)|Don Oakes]] (1928\u20131977), professional footballer ([[Arsenal F.C.]])\n*[[Nathan Penlington]] (living), writer, poet and magician\n*[[Mike Peters (musician)|Michael Leslie Peters]] (born 1959), lead singer and founding member of the group ''[[The Alarm]]'', born in [[Prestatyn]], grew up in Rhyl, attending Rhyl High School.\n*[[William Roberts (footballer, born 1863)|William Roberts]] (born 1863, fl. 1880s \u2013 1890s), international footballer\n*[[Lisa Scott-Lee]] (born 1975), singer and dancer\n*[[Steve Strange]] (1959\u20132015), pop musician\n*[[Sara Sugarman]] (born 1962), actress and film director\n*[[Carol Vorderman]] (born 1960), TV broadcaster and game-show host, attended Rhyl's Blessed Edward Jones High School\n*[[Edward Ross Wharton]] (1844\u20131896), classical scholar, etymologist and lexicographer<ref>Bibliography backing description: [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/webbin/book/lookupname?key=Wharton%2C%20Edward%20Ross%2C%201844-1896 Retrieved 7 February 2017.]</ref>\n*[[Spencer Wilding]] (born 1972), actor best known for Darth Vader in ''[[Rogue One]]''\n*[[Vernon R. Young]] (1937\u20132004), research scientist specializing in [[protein]] and [[amino acid]] requirements\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Rhyl}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Rhyl}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northeast/sites/rhyl_town/ BBC Rhyl page]\n*[http://rhyltowncouncil.org.uk/ Rhyl town council page]\n\n{{Denbighshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rhyl| ]]\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in Wales]]\n[[Category:Towns in Denbighshire]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Bmcln1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhyl"}
{"title_page": "Cyclone Erica", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name=Severe Tropical Cyclone Erica\n| Type=Tropical cyclone\n| Year=2003\n| Basin=SPac\n| Image location=Cyclone Erica 13 mar 2003 0255Z.jpg\n| Image name=Cyclone Erica near its peak intensity on March 13, northwest of New Caledonia\n| Formed=1 March 2003\n| Extratropical=15 March\n| Dissipated=17 March 2003\n| 10-min winds=115\n| 1-min winds=130\n| Pressure=915\n| Damages=15\n| Fatalities=2 total\n| Areas=[[Queensland]], Southeast [[Papua New Guinea]], [[Solomon Islands]], [[New Caledonia]]\n| Hurricane season=[[2002\u201303 Australian region cyclone season|2002\u201303 Australian region]] and [[2002\u201303 South Pacific cyclone season|South Pacific cyclone seasons]]\n}}\n'''Severe Tropical Cyclone Erica''' of March 2003 was a powerful cyclone that severely affected [[New Caledonia]] and was considered the worst to affect the country since [[1995\u201396 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Beti|Cyclone Beti]]. The system was the eighth cyclone and the fifth severe tropical cyclone of the [[2002-03 South Pacific cyclone season]]. Cyclone Erica developed from a [[monsoon]]al [[trough (meteorology)|trough]] on 4 March just off of [[Queensland]]. Originally, the storm moved slowly towards the east and then north early in its existence. However, increasing [[wind shear]] caused the storm to be degenerated into a [[tropical low]]. After conditions once again became more favorable for development, the remnants regenerated into a tropical cyclone on 10 March. Steadily intensifying, Erica reached peak intensity on 13 March as a Category 5 equivalent on the [[Tropical cyclone scales#Australia and Fiji|Australian intensity scale]].\n\nOn the same day Erica paralleled the coast of New Caledonia before making landfall on the southern end of the island at [[L'\u00cele-des-Pins]]. However, at the same time the cyclone also entered an area with strong wind shear and thus began to weaken. After passing the island, an [[extratropical transition]] begun, weakening the cyclone as it moved towards the southeast. On 15 March, Erica completed its transition into an [[extratropical cyclone]] and later fully dissipated two days later.\n\nCyclone Erica severely impacted the island nation of New Caledonia, causing intense winds and heavy rain. An estimated 892 families were affected by the cyclone on the island, and two people were killed. As many as 60% of people on the west coast [[power outage|lost power]]. On 17 March only 17 of the 66 [[secondary school]]s on the island were functioning. After the storm it was feared that the existing [[dengue fever]] [[epidemic]] on the island would spread. Erica caused $15 million (2003&nbsp;USD) in damages, primarily on New Caledonia. Following the deaths and damage, the name \"Erica\" was later retired.\n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{Storm path|Erica 2003 track.png}}\nSevere Tropical Cyclone Erica's precursor tropical low initially developed within a [[monsoon]] [[trough (meteorology)|trough]] near the [[Tiwi Islands]] on 13 February.<ref name=\"March 2003\">{{cite web|title=Monthly Global Tropical Cyclone Summary March 2003 |url=http://www.australiansevereweather.com/cyclones/2003/summ0303.htm |accessdate=26 August 2012 |author=Padget, Gary |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vy2pM0uM?url=http://www.australiansevereweather.com/cyclones/2003/summ0303.htm |archivedate=24 January 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Over the next couple of days, the low moved south-southwest into the Joseph Bonaparte Gulf, before it made landfall near the [[Western Australia]]\u2013[[Northern Territory]] border during 15 February.<ref name=\"March 2003\"/> Over the next couple of weeks, the low moved across the Australian interior and passed to the south of [[Alice Springs, Northern Territory|Alice Springs]].<ref name=\"March 2003\"/> It subsequently moved northwards towards Mount Isa in Queensland, before it started to move eastwards and entered the Coral Sea near the Whitsunday Islands during 3 March.<ref name=\"March 2003\"/> \n\nStrong [[wind shear]] separated the [[Atmospheric convection|convection]] from the system at the time. However, shear quickly weakened the next day. With the lower shear, the low was able to intensify<ref name=\"TCRNadi\">{{cite report|title=Tropical Cyclone Seasonal Summary 2002-2003 season |url=http://www.met.gov.fj/documents/TC_Seasonal_Summary_02-031190690457.pdf |accessdate=13 October 2012 |author=RSMC Nadi&nbsp;\u2014 Tropical Cyclone Centre |publisher=Fiji Meteorological Service |format=PDF |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rXVeMgCD?url=http://www.met.gov.fj/documents/TC_Seasonal_Summary_02-031190690457.pdf |archivedate=27 July 2010 |date=29 August 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> and at 0630&nbsp;[[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]] on 4 March, the [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] (JTWC) issued a [[tropical cyclone formation alert]]. Despite the center of the storm being elongated, conditions for further development were present.<ref name=\"JTWC advisories\">{{cite web|author=[[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]]|publisher=Australian Severe Weather|date=17 March 2003|accessdate=7 January 2009|title=Joint Typhoon Warning Center Advisories on Tropical Cyclone Erica|url=http://www.australiasevereweather.com/cyclones/2003/erica.htm}}</ref> At 0600&nbsp;UTC the [[Bureau of Meteorology (Australia)|Bureau of Meteorology in Australia]] upgraded the low to a Category&nbsp;1 cyclone and gave it the name ''Erica''.<ref name=\"TCRNadi\"/>\n\nAs Erica moved towards the south and subsequently to the north, the cyclone strengthened, becoming equivalent to a tropical storm according to the JTWC by 1500&nbsp;UTC on 5 March.<ref name=\"JTWC advisories\" /> Erica later attained [[maximum sustained wind]]s of 105&nbsp;km/h (65&nbsp;mph <small>1-minute sustained</small>). However the system began to move against the direction of the wind shear environment, and it lost much of its organization. On 7 March at 2230&nbsp;UTC, Erica lost cyclone status and degenerated into a [[tropical low]]. The remnant circulation moved slowly to the northeast, and the wind shear conditions abated. As a result, Erica began to gain some signs of organization. At this time the remnants moved towards the southeast as a result of an upper-level trough developing over Australia.<ref name=gpsummary>{{cite web|title=Monthly Global Tropical Cyclone Summary March 2003 |url=http://www.australiansevereweather.com/cyclones/2003/summ0303.htm |publisher=Australian Severe Weather Index |accessdate=26 August 2012 |author=Padget, Gary |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vy2pM0uM?url=http://www.australiansevereweather.com/cyclones/2003/summ0303.htm |archivedate=24 January 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Erica and Eseta 11 mar 2003 2330Z.jpg|thumb|Cyclones Erica (left) and Eseta (right) on March 11.|alt=Satellite image of two simultaneous tropical cyclones, both with similar appearances.]]\nThe area of low pressure gained sufficient shower activity and organization to be renamed as a tropical cyclone at 1800&nbsp;UTC on 10 March while located southwest of the [[Solomon Islands]] capital of [[Honiara]]. Erica gradually intensified, attaining the equivalent to a [[Category 1 hurricane]] on the [[Saffir\u2013Simpson Hurricane Scale]] <small>(SSHS)</small> Originally moving to the southeast at a slow pace, Erica began to accelerate due to the influence of weak [[ridge (meteorology)|mid\u2013level ridge]] to its east. Continuing to intensify, the cyclone reached its peak intensity on 13 March with a minimum [[barometric pressure]] of {{convert|915|mbar|inHg|abbr=on}}, and peak winds of 250&nbsp;km/h (150&nbsp;mph <small>1-minute sustained</small>). The [[eye (cyclone)|eye]] of the cyclone began to shrink in diameter and become symmetrical. Later on 13 March, Erica began to parallel the western coast of [[New Caledonia]] while maintaining a strong intensity, before crossing the extreme southern end of the island at the Caledonian island [[commune]] of [[L'\u00cele-des-Pins]].<ref name=gpsummary />\n\nAfter passing the island, Erica accelerated and began to rapidly weaken in the presence of strong wind shear. As a result, the cyclone began a phase of [[extratropical transition]] as it quickly paced to the southeast. On 15 March, Erica completed this transition.<ref name=gpsummary /> The remnant low continued to the east-southeast, ultimately dissipating on 17&nbsp;March.<ref name=\"dbt\">{{cite report|author=Kenneth R. Knapp|author2=Michael C. Kruk|author3=David H. Levinson|author4=Howard J. Diamond|author5=Charles J. Neumann|year=2020|work=The International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship (IBTrACS): Unifying tropical cyclone best track data|title=2003 Tropical Cyclone Erica (2003061S21148)|publisher=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|accessdate=7 April 2020|url=http://ibtracs.unca.edu/index.php?name=v04r00-2003061S21148&fbclid=IwAR0bHMP3wxfgcCM7YqISv86kx8UEG9tdR-EIVX59z-_oJhVCOALHk53VKs4}}</ref>\n\n==Preparations, impact, and aftermath==\n[[File:TC Erica 04 mar 2003 0305Z.jpg|thumb|left|Erica on 4 March 2003|alt=A satellite image of a developing tropical cyclone. Rainbands can be seen swirling into the cyclone]]\n\n=== Australia ===\nAs a tropical low, Erica brought strong winds to northern [[Queensland]]. Several large trees were uprooted, one of which fell on a car in [[Cape Tribulation]] and another on a house in [[Port Douglas, Queensland|Port Douglas]]. Numerous trees were defoliated and some boats were reported to have been pulling their moorings due to the wind. Power lines were also damaged by the low.<ref name=\"SS\">{{cite report|format=PDF |archivedate=27 July 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rXVeMgCD?url=http://www.met.gov.fj/documents/TC_Seasonal_Summary_02-031190690457.pdf |url=http://www.met.gov.fj/documents/TC_Seasonal_Summary_02-031190690457.pdf |author=RSMC Nadi&nbsp;\u2014 Tropical Cyclone Centre |accessdate=27 June 2010 |title=Tropical Cyclone Seasonal Summary 2002\u201303 |publisher=Fiji Meteorological Service |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== New Caledonia ===\nOn 12 March, officials in [[New Caledonia]] issued a pre-alert as Erica was forecast to impact the territory. Evacuation centers were set up in churches and community halls.<ref name=\"RNZ1\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=Radio New Zealand International|date=12 March 2003|accessdate=6 January 2009|title=New Caledonia sounds alert as Cyclone Erica heads towards the territory|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=3971}}</ref> All schools throughout the island were closed and airports were shut down.<ref name=\"RNZ2\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=Radio New Zealand|date=13 March 2003|accessdate=17 March 2009|title=Cyclone Erica hits northern New Caledonia, Eseta strikes Tonga|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=3983}}</ref>\n\nDespite the rapid weakening before landfall, Erica produced intense winds, gusting to a record 202&nbsp;km/h (125&nbsp;mph) in [[Noum\u00e9a]]. [[Maximum sustained wind|Ten-minute sustained winds]] were recorded up to 144&nbsp;km/h (89&nbsp;mph) around the center of the storm.\n\nAn estimated 892 families were affected by Erica, and Erica was also reported to have caused two deaths and injured 80 people.<ref name=repairsunderway>{{cite news|title=Repairs underway in New Caledonia after devastation of Cyclone Erica|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=4009|accessdate=25 August 2012|newspaper=Radio New Zealand International|date=16 March 2003|publisher=Radio New Zealand International}}</ref> In addition 1,000 people were estimated to be [[homeless]].<ref name=OCHAno1>{{cite news|title=Tropical cyclone OCHA Situation Report No. 1|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/new-caledonia-france/new-caledonia-tropical-cyclone-ocha-situation-report-no-1|accessdate=13 October 2012|date=17 March 2003|author=UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs|agency=ReliefWeb}}</ref>   Several communication lines were severed, and tribes and farms were devastated.<ref name=cgt>{{cite web|title=Le cyclone Erica a ravag\u00e9 la Nouelle Cal\u00e9donie|url=http://www.cgt.fr/Le-cyclone-Erica-a-ravage-la.html|publisher=La CGT Societ\u00e9|accessdate=25 August 2012|language=French|date=11 August 2004}}</ref>  20% of electricity customers in Noum\u00e9a were without power, and 60% of customers on the main island's west coast were also without power.<ref name=ncassess2>{{cite web|title=New Caledonia assesses the damage after two killed in cyclone|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/new-caledonia-france/new-caledonia-assesses-damage-after-two-killed-cyclone|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=25 August 2012|author=Agence France-Presse|date=15 March 2003}}</ref>  In [[Yat\u00e9]], police assessed that half of the population was without shelter, and in Poh\u00e9, it was estimated that 90% of the crops were destroyed by Erica.<ref name=thousandshomeless>{{cite web|title=Thousands homeless after New Caledonia cyclone|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/new-caledonia-france/thousands-homeless-after-new-caledonia-cyclone|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=25 August 2012|author=[[East\u2013West Center]]|date=18 March 2003}}</ref><ref name=25milfrance>{{cite web|title=France OKs $25 million for New Caledonia housing|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/new-caledonia-france/france-oks-25-million-new-caledonia-housing|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=25 August 2012|author=East-West Center|date=20 March 2003}}</ref>  On 17 March 2003, only 17 of the 66 [[secondary school]]s in New Caledonia were functioning, with others still closed primarily due to safety concerns. The [[University of New Caledonia]] was also badly damaged. However, all [[primary school]]s were functioning.<ref name=thousandshomeless />\n\n[[South Province, New Caledonia]] formed an emergency committee following the storm, led by Jacques Lafleur. The committee assisted in filing damage claims caused by the cyclone.<ref name=ncassesses>{{cite news|title=New Caledonia still assessing the impact of Cyclone Erica|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=4023|accessdate=25 August 2012|publisher=Radio New Zealand International|date=17 March 2003}}</ref> After the storm, 60 French specialists were sent to New Caledonia to help in rebuilding areas hit hard by Erica. [[Ministry of Overseas France]] head Brigitte Giradin arrived in Noum\u00e9a on 17&nbsp;March to investigate the damage.<ref name=francespecialists>{{cite news|title=France sends 60 specialists to New Caledonia after cyclone Erica|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=4027|accessdate=25 August 2012|publisher=[[Radio New Zealand International]]|date=17 March 2003|location=[[Wellington, New Zealand]]}}</ref> Following the visit, Brigitte Giradin announced that US$17 million would be sent to rebuild 1,000 homes on the island nation, including an additional [[United States dollar|US]]$500,000 in disaster relief to the island country.<ref name=25milfrance /><ref name=frenchministers>{{cite news|title=French minister tours cyclone-ravaged New Caledonia|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=4047|accessdate=25 August 2012|publisher=Radio New Zealand International|date=18 March 2003}}</ref> A transport aircraft stationed in [[Tahiti]] brought {{convert|1.5|ST|kg|abbr=on}} of emergency supplies.<ref name=thousandshomeless />\n\nFollowing Erica's heavy rains, it was feared that the already existing [[dengue fever]] [[epidemic]] would become more widespread. Prior to Erica, there were already 437 cases of dengue fever in 2003 alone. The risk for [[leptospirosis]] was also increased by Erica.<ref name=denguethreat>{{cite web|title=Cyclone raises dengue threat in New Caledonia|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/new-caledonia-france/cyclone-raises-dengue-threat-new-caledonia|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=25 August 2012|author=East-West Center|date=24 March 2003}}</ref> High winds and strong rains resulted in damages of at least US$15 million, particularly to schools. Two fatalities total were reported as a result of Erica.<ref name=TCRNadi /> The name ''Erica'' was retired after the season.{{RA V Tropical cyclone operational plan}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[Cyclone Beni]]\n*[[Cyclone Ivy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cyclone Erica}}\n{{SPAC EL's}}\n\n{{2002-03 South Pacific cyclone season buttons}}\n{{Retired Australian cyclones}}\n{{Category 3 Australian region tropical cyclones}}\n{{Category 5 South Pacific severe tropical cyclones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erica (2003)}}\n[[Category:Retired Australian region cyclones]]\n[[Category:Tropical cyclones in New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Category 5 South Pacific cyclones]]\n[[Category:2002\u201303 Australian region cyclone season]]\n[[Category:2002\u201303 South Pacific cyclone season]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox Hurricane\n| Name=Severe Tropical Cyclone Erica\n| Type=Tropical cyclone\n| Year=2003\n| Basin=SPac\n| Image location=Cyclone Erica 13 mar 2003 0255Z.jpg\n| Image name=Cyclone Erica near its peak intensity on March 13, northwest of New Caledonia\n| Formed=1 March 2003\n| Extratropical=15 March\n| Dissipated=17 March 2003\n| 10-min winds=115\n| 1-min winds=130\n| Pressure=915\n| Damages=15\n| Fatalities=2 total\n| Areas=[[Queensland]], Southeast [[Papua New Guinea]], [[Solomon Islands]], [[New Caledonia]]\n| Hurricane season=[[2002\u201303 Australian region cyclone season|2002\u201303 Australian region]] and [[2002\u201303 South Pacific cyclone season|South Pacific cyclone seasons]]\n}}\n'''Severe Tropical Cyclone Erica''' of March 2003 was a powerful cyclone that severely affected [[New Caledonia]] and was considered the worst to affect the country since [[1995\u201396 South Pacific cyclone season#Severe Tropical Cyclone Beti|Cyclone Beti]]. The system was the eighth cyclone and the fifth severe tropical cyclone of the [[2002-03 South Pacific cyclone season]]. Cyclone Erica developed from a [[monsoon]]al [[trough (meteorology)|trough]] on 4 March just off of [[Queensland]]. Originally, the storm moved slowly towards the east and then north early in its existence. However, increasing [[wind shear]] caused the storm to be degenerated into a [[tropical low]]. After conditions once again became more favorable for development, the remnants regenerated into a tropical cyclone on 10 March. Steadily intensifying, Erica reached peak intensity on 13 March as a Category 5 equivalent on the [[Tropical cyclone scales#Australia and Fiji|Australian intensity scale]].\n\nOn the same day Erica paralleled the coast of New Caledonia before making landfall on the southern end of the island at [[L'\u00cele-des-Pins]]. However, at the same time the cyclone also entered an area with strong wind shear and thus began to weaken. After passing the island, an [[extratropical transition]] begun, weakening the cyclone as it moved towards the southeast. On 15 March, Erica completed its transition into an [[extratropical cyclone]] and later fully dissipated two days later.\n\nCyclone Erica severely impacted the island nation of New Caledonia, causing intense winds and heavy rain. An estimated 892 families were affected by the cyclone on the island, and two people were killed. As many as 60% of people on the west coast [[power outage|lost power]]. On 17 March only 17 of the 66 [[secondary school]]s on the island were functioning. After the storm it was feared that the existing [[dengue fever]] [[epidemic]] on the island would spread. Erica caused $15 million (2003&nbsp;USD) in damages, primarily on New Caledonia. Following the deaths and damage, the name \"Erica\" was later retired.\n\n==Meteorological history==\n{{Storm path|Erica 2003 track.png}}\nSevere Tropical Cyclone Erica's precursor tropical low initially developed within a [[monsoon]] [[trough (meteorology)|trough]] near the [[Tiwi Islands]] on 13 February.<ref name=\"March 2003\">{{cite web|title=Monthly Global Tropical Cyclone Summary March 2003 |url=http://www.australiansevereweather.com/cyclones/2003/summ0303.htm |accessdate=26 August 2012 |author=Padget, Gary |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vy2pM0uM?url=http://www.australiansevereweather.com/cyclones/2003/summ0303.htm |archivedate=24 January 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Over the next couple of days, the low moved south-southwest into the Joseph Bonaparte Gulf, before it made landfall near the [[Western Australia]]\u2013[[Northern Territory]] border during 15 February.<ref name=\"March 2003\"/> Over the next couple of weeks, the low moved across the Australian interior and passed to the south of [[Alice Springs, Northern Territory|Alice Springs]].<ref name=\"March 2003\"/> It subsequently moved northwards towards Mount Isa in Queensland, before it started to move eastwards and entered the Coral Sea near the Whitsunday Islands during 3 March.<ref name=\"March 2003\"/> \n\nStrong [[wind shear]] separated the [[Atmospheric convection|convection]] from the system at the time. However, shear quickly weakened the next day. With the lower shear, the low was able to intensify<ref name=\"TCRNadi\">{{cite report|title=Tropical Cyclone Seasonal Summary 2002-2003 season |url=http://www.met.gov.fj/documents/TC_Seasonal_Summary_02-031190690457.pdf |accessdate=13 October 2012 |author=RSMC Nadi&nbsp;\u2014 Tropical Cyclone Centre |publisher=Fiji Meteorological Service |format=PDF |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rXVeMgCD?url=http://www.met.gov.fj/documents/TC_Seasonal_Summary_02-031190690457.pdf |archivedate=27 July 2010 |date=29 August 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> and at 0630&nbsp;[[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]] on 4 March, the [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] (JTWC) issued a [[tropical cyclone formation alert]]. Despite the center of the storm being elongated, conditions for further development were present.<ref name=\"JTWC advisories\">{{cite web|author=[[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]]|publisher=Australian Severe Weather|date=17 March 2003|accessdate=7 January 2009|title=Joint Typhoon Warning Center Advisories on Tropical Cyclone Erica|url=http://www.australiasevereweather.com/cyclones/2003/erica.htm}}</ref> At 0600&nbsp;UTC the [[Bureau of Meteorology (Australia)|Bureau of Meteorology in Australia]] upgraded the low to a Category&nbsp;1 cyclone and gave it the name ''Erica''.<ref name=\"TCRNadi\"/>\n\nAs Erica moved towards the south and subsequently to the north, the cyclone strengthened, becoming equivalent to a tropical storm according to the JTWC by 1500&nbsp;UTC on 5 March.<ref name=\"JTWC advisories\" /> Erica later attained [[maximum sustained wind]]s of 105&nbsp;km/h (65&nbsp;mph <small>1-minute sustained</small>). However the system began to move against the direction of the wind shear environment, and it lost much of its organization. On 7 March at 2230&nbsp;UTC, Erica lost cyclone status and degenerated into a [[tropical low]]. The remnant circulation moved slowly to the northeast, and the wind shear conditions abated. As a result, Erica began to gain some signs of organization. At this time the remnants moved towards the southeast as a result of an upper-level trough developing over Australia.<ref name=gpsummary>{{cite web|title=Monthly Global Tropical Cyclone Summary March 2003 |url=http://www.australiansevereweather.com/cyclones/2003/summ0303.htm |publisher=Australian Severe Weather Index |accessdate=26 August 2012 |author=Padget, Gary |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vy2pM0uM?url=http://www.australiansevereweather.com/cyclones/2003/summ0303.htm |archivedate=24 January 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Erica and Eseta 11 mar 2003 2330Z.jpg|thumb|Cyclones Erica (left) and Eseta (right) on March 11.|alt=Satellite image of two simultaneous tropical cyclones, both with similar appearances.]]\nThe area of low pressure gained sufficient shower activity and organization to be renamed as a tropical cyclone at 1800&nbsp;UTC on 10 March while located southwest of the [[Solomon Islands]] capital of [[Honiara]]. Erica gradually intensified, attaining the equivalent to a [[Category 1 hurricane]] on the [[Saffir\u2013Simpson Hurricane Scale]] <small>(SSHS)</small> Originally moving to the southeast at a slow pace, Erica began to accelerate due to the influence of weak [[ridge (meteorology)|mid\u2013level ridge]] to its east. Continuing to intensify, the cyclone reached its peak intensity on 13 March with a minimum [[barometric pressure]] of {{convert|915|mbar|inHg|abbr=on}}, and peak winds of 260&nbsp;km/h (150&nbsp;mph <small>1-minute sustained</small>). The [[eye (cyclone)|eye]] of the cyclone began to shrink in diameter and become symmetrical. Later on 13 March, Erica began to parallel the western coast of [[New Caledonia]] while maintaining a strong intensity, before crossing the extreme southern end of the island at the Caledonian island [[commune]] of [[L'\u00cele-des-Pins]].<ref name=gpsummary />\n\nAfter passing the island, Erica accelerated and began to rapidly weaken in the presence of strong wind shear. As a result, the cyclone began a phase of [[extratropical transition]] as it quickly paced to the southeast. On 15 March, Erica completed this transition.<ref name=gpsummary /> The remnant low continued to the east-southeast, ultimately dissipating on 17&nbsp;March.<ref name=\"dbt\">{{cite report|author=Kenneth R. Knapp|author2=Michael C. Kruk|author3=David H. Levinson|author4=Howard J. Diamond|author5=Charles J. Neumann|year=2020|work=The International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship (IBTrACS): Unifying tropical cyclone best track data|title=2003 Tropical Cyclone Erica (2003061S21148)|publisher=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|accessdate=7 April 2020|url=http://ibtracs.unca.edu/index.php?name=v04r00-2003061S21148&fbclid=IwAR0bHMP3wxfgcCM7YqISv86kx8UEG9tdR-EIVX59z-_oJhVCOALHk53VKs4}}</ref>\n\n==Preparations, impact, and aftermath==\n[[File:TC Erica 04 mar 2003 0305Z.jpg|thumb|left|Erica on 4 March 2003|alt=A satellite image of a developing tropical cyclone. Rainbands can be seen swirling into the cyclone]]\n\n=== Australia ===\nAs a tropical low, Erica brought strong winds to northern [[Queensland]]. Several large trees were uprooted, one of which fell on a car in [[Cape Tribulation]] and another on a house in [[Port Douglas, Queensland|Port Douglas]]. Numerous trees were defoliated and some boats were reported to have been pulling their moorings due to the wind. Power lines were also damaged by the low.<ref name=\"SS\">{{cite report|format=PDF |archivedate=27 July 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rXVeMgCD?url=http://www.met.gov.fj/documents/TC_Seasonal_Summary_02-031190690457.pdf |url=http://www.met.gov.fj/documents/TC_Seasonal_Summary_02-031190690457.pdf |author=RSMC Nadi&nbsp;\u2014 Tropical Cyclone Centre |accessdate=27 June 2010 |title=Tropical Cyclone Seasonal Summary 2002\u201303 |publisher=Fiji Meteorological Service |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== New Caledonia ===\nOn 12 March, officials in [[New Caledonia]] issued a pre-alert as Erica was forecast to impact the territory. Evacuation centers were set up in churches and community halls.<ref name=\"RNZ1\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=Radio New Zealand International|date=12 March 2003|accessdate=6 January 2009|title=New Caledonia sounds alert as Cyclone Erica heads towards the territory|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=3971}}</ref> All schools throughout the island were closed and airports were shut down.<ref name=\"RNZ2\">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=Radio New Zealand|date=13 March 2003|accessdate=17 March 2009|title=Cyclone Erica hits northern New Caledonia, Eseta strikes Tonga|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=3983}}</ref>\n\nDespite the rapid weakening before landfall, Erica produced intense winds, gusting to a record 202&nbsp;km/h (125&nbsp;mph) in [[Noum\u00e9a]]. [[Maximum sustained wind|Ten-minute sustained winds]] were recorded up to 144&nbsp;km/h (89&nbsp;mph) around the center of the storm.\n\nAn estimated 892 families were affected by Erica, and Erica was also reported to have caused two deaths and injured 80 people.<ref name=repairsunderway>{{cite news|title=Repairs underway in New Caledonia after devastation of Cyclone Erica|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=4009|accessdate=25 August 2012|newspaper=Radio New Zealand International|date=16 March 2003|publisher=Radio New Zealand International}}</ref> In addition 1,000 people were estimated to be [[homeless]].<ref name=OCHAno1>{{cite news|title=Tropical cyclone OCHA Situation Report No. 1|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/new-caledonia-france/new-caledonia-tropical-cyclone-ocha-situation-report-no-1|accessdate=13 October 2012|date=17 March 2003|author=UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs|agency=ReliefWeb}}</ref>   Several communication lines were severed, and tribes and farms were devastated.<ref name=cgt>{{cite web|title=Le cyclone Erica a ravag\u00e9 la Nouelle Cal\u00e9donie|url=http://www.cgt.fr/Le-cyclone-Erica-a-ravage-la.html|publisher=La CGT Societ\u00e9|accessdate=25 August 2012|language=French|date=11 August 2004}}</ref>  20% of electricity customers in Noum\u00e9a were without power, and 60% of customers on the main island's west coast were also without power.<ref name=ncassess2>{{cite web|title=New Caledonia assesses the damage after two killed in cyclone|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/new-caledonia-france/new-caledonia-assesses-damage-after-two-killed-cyclone|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=25 August 2012|author=Agence France-Presse|date=15 March 2003}}</ref>  In [[Yat\u00e9]], police assessed that half of the population was without shelter, and in Poh\u00e9, it was estimated that 90% of the crops were destroyed by Erica.<ref name=thousandshomeless>{{cite web|title=Thousands homeless after New Caledonia cyclone|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/new-caledonia-france/thousands-homeless-after-new-caledonia-cyclone|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=25 August 2012|author=[[East\u2013West Center]]|date=18 March 2003}}</ref><ref name=25milfrance>{{cite web|title=France OKs $25 million for New Caledonia housing|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/new-caledonia-france/france-oks-25-million-new-caledonia-housing|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=25 August 2012|author=East-West Center|date=20 March 2003}}</ref>  On 17 March 2003, only 17 of the 66 [[secondary school]]s in New Caledonia were functioning, with others still closed primarily due to safety concerns. The [[University of New Caledonia]] was also badly damaged. However, all [[primary school]]s were functioning.<ref name=thousandshomeless />\n\n[[South Province, New Caledonia]] formed an emergency committee following the storm, led by Jacques Lafleur. The committee assisted in filing damage claims caused by the cyclone.<ref name=ncassesses>{{cite news|title=New Caledonia still assessing the impact of Cyclone Erica|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=4023|accessdate=25 August 2012|publisher=Radio New Zealand International|date=17 March 2003}}</ref> After the storm, 60 French specialists were sent to New Caledonia to help in rebuilding areas hit hard by Erica. [[Ministry of Overseas France]] head Brigitte Giradin arrived in Noum\u00e9a on 17&nbsp;March to investigate the damage.<ref name=francespecialists>{{cite news|title=France sends 60 specialists to New Caledonia after cyclone Erica|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=4027|accessdate=25 August 2012|publisher=[[Radio New Zealand International]]|date=17 March 2003|location=[[Wellington, New Zealand]]}}</ref> Following the visit, Brigitte Giradin announced that US$17 million would be sent to rebuild 1,000 homes on the island nation, including an additional [[United States dollar|US]]$500,000 in disaster relief to the island country.<ref name=25milfrance /><ref name=frenchministers>{{cite news|title=French minister tours cyclone-ravaged New Caledonia|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=4047|accessdate=25 August 2012|publisher=Radio New Zealand International|date=18 March 2003}}</ref> A transport aircraft stationed in [[Tahiti]] brought {{convert|1.5|ST|kg|abbr=on}} of emergency supplies.<ref name=thousandshomeless />\n\nFollowing Erica's heavy rains, it was feared that the already existing [[dengue fever]] [[epidemic]] would become more widespread. Prior to Erica, there were already 437 cases of dengue fever in 2003 alone. The risk for [[leptospirosis]] was also increased by Erica.<ref name=denguethreat>{{cite web|title=Cyclone raises dengue threat in New Caledonia|url=http://reliefweb.int/report/new-caledonia-france/cyclone-raises-dengue-threat-new-caledonia|publisher=ReliefWeb|accessdate=25 August 2012|author=East-West Center|date=24 March 2003}}</ref> High winds and strong rains resulted in damages of at least US$15 million, particularly to schools. Two fatalities total were reported as a result of Erica.<ref name=TCRNadi /> The name ''Erica'' was retired after the season.{{RA V Tropical cyclone operational plan}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[Cyclone Beni]]\n*[[Cyclone Ivy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cyclone Erica}}\n{{SPAC EL's}}\n\n{{2002-03 South Pacific cyclone season buttons}}\n{{Retired Australian cyclones}}\n{{Category 3 Australian region tropical cyclones}}\n{{Category 5 South Pacific severe tropical cyclones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erica (2003)}}\n[[Category:Retired Australian region cyclones]]\n[[Category:Tropical cyclones in New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Category 5 South Pacific cyclones]]\n[[Category:2002\u201303 Australian region cyclone season]]\n[[Category:2002\u201303 South Pacific cyclone season]]\n", "name_user": "Cyclonebiskit", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMeteorological history:correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclone_Erica"}
{"title_page": "David Crane (lawyer)", "text_new": "'''David M. Crane''' is an [[United States|American]] lawyer who was the Chief Prosecutor of the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]] (SCSL) from April 2002 until July 15, 2005. During his tenure, he indicted, among others, the then-[[President of Liberia]], [[Charles Taylor (Liberian politician)|Charles Taylor]]. Crane was replaced as chief prosecutor by his deputy [[Sir Desmond Lorenz de Silva|Desmond de Silva]].  On April 26, 2012, the SCSL, sitting in The Hague, convicted Taylor on various charges.\n\n==Early life and education==\nCrane has a law degree from [[Syracuse University College of Law]] and a M.A. in African Studies from [[Ohio University]].\n\n==Career==\nCrane spent 30 years working for the [[United States federal government]]. His former posts include Director of the [[Office of Intelligence Review]], assistant general counsel of the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] and the Waldemar A. Solf Professor of [[International Law]] at the [[United States Army]] Judge Advocate Generals School.\n\nCrane served as Professor of Practice at [[Syracuse University College of Law]] from 2006 until 2018.<ref>[http://law.syr.edu/news_events/news/professor-of-practice-david-m.-crane-l80-announces-retirement Professor of Practice David M. Crane L\u201980 Announces Retirement from the College of Law] [[Syracuse University College of Law]], press release of March 30, 2018.</ref> He taught international criminal law, international law, national security law, and the law of armed conflict.<ref name=\"David Crane\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beloit.edu/oie/campus_internat/crane.htm|title=David Crane|accessdate=2009-06-29}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"Professor of Practice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.law.syr.edu/faculty/facultymember.aspx?fac=152|title=David M. Crane - Professor of Practice|accessdate=2009-06-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609193355/http://law.syr.edu/faculty/facultymember.aspx?fac=152|archivedate=2010-06-09}}</ref>\n\nIn conjunction with Syracuse University College of Law students, Crane started [[Impunity Watch]], an online publication which seeks to inform the world of human rights violations in real-time. Another Syracuse University College of Law project is the Syria Accountability Project (SAP). SAP was begun in 2011 as a project of Crane\u2019s International Legal Practice course at SU Law and now involves 50 SU law students. SAP works collectively with several international organizations to provide impartial analysis of open source materials so that [[Bashar al-Assad|President Bashar al-Assad]] and his subordinates\u2014as well as members of the Syrian opposition\u2014can be prosecuted openly and fairly under the [[Geneva Conventions]], the [[Rome Statute]], and/or Syrian Penal Law.<ref name=\"dailyorange.com\">http://dailyorange.com/2013/10/professor-to-testify-about-syrian-war-crimes/</ref>\n\nFollowing his time as founding Chief Prosecutor of the Special Court for Sierra Leone, Crane and his fellow prosecutors DeSilva and [[Brenda Hollis]] traveled to [[The Hague]], [[Netherlands]] on September 26, 2013 to witness the upholding of Taylor\u2019s 50-year sentence by the special court\u2019s appeals judges.<ref>http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/26/world/africa/netherlands-charles-taylor-verdict/index.html?iref=allsearch</ref> On October 29, 2013 Crane testified in front of the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]] Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights, and International Organizations about the possible establishment of a Syrian War Crimes Tribunal.<ref name=\"dailyorange.com\"/> He later co-authored the [[2014 Syrian detainee report]].\n\nIn July 2018, the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] appointed Crane to co-chair (alongside [[Sara Hossain]] and [[Kaari Betty Murungi]]) a three-person Commission of Inquiry into the killing of at least 140 Palestinians by the Israeli army.<ref>Tom Miles (July 25, 2018), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-palestinans-un/u-n-picks-american-to-lead-investigation-into-gaza-protest-killings-idUSKBN1KF244 U.N. picks American to lead investigation into Gaza protest killings] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref> Already one month later, he resigned \u201cdue to a personal circumstance that has arisen.\u201d<ref>Toby Sterling (August 23, 2018), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-palestinians-un/chair-of-u-n-probe-of-gaza-violence-quits-less-than-month-into-job-idUSKCN1L811K Chair of U.N. probe of Gaza violence quits less than month into job] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref>\n\nHe is currently a member of the [[Crimes Against Humanity Initiative]] Advisory Council, a project of the [[Whitney R. Harris World Law Institute]] at [[Washington University in St. Louis | Washington University School of Law in St. Louis]] to establish the world\u2019s first treaty on the prevention and punishment of crimes against humanity.\n\n==Other activities==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190109000747/http://www.roberthjackson.org/ Robert H. Jackson Center], Chairman of the Board (2012-2015), Board Director (2012-present) \n* [[International Peace and Security Institute]], Member of the Board of Directors\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120427173235/http://www.sc-sl.org/ Special Court for Sierra Leone web site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130823212039/http://www.law.syr.edu/deans-faculty-staff/profile.aspx?fac=152 Syracuse University College of Law faculty listing and biography]\n*[http://legal.un.org/avl/faculty/Crane.html See forthcoming lectures in the Lecture Series of the United Nations Audiovisual Library of International Law]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crane, David}}\n[[Category:Special Court for Sierra Leone prosecutors]]\n[[Category:American lawyers]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University faculty]]\n[[Category:Ohio University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''David M. Crane''' is an [[United States|American]] lawyer who was the Chief Prosecutor of the [[Special Court for Sierra Leone]] (SCSL) from April 2002 until July 15, 2005. During his tenure, he indicted, among others, the then-[[President of Liberia]], [[Charles Taylor (Liberian politician)|Charles Taylor]]. Crane was replaced as chief prosecutor by his deputy [[Sir Desmond Lorenz de Silva|Desmond de Silva]].  On April 26, 2012, the SCSL, sitting in The Hague, convicted Taylor on various charges.\n\n==Early life and education==\nCrane has a law degree from [[Syracuse University College of Law]] and a M.A. in African Studies from [[Ohio University]].\n\n==Career==\nCrane spent 30 years working for the [[United States federal government]]. His former posts include Director of the [[Office of Intelligence Review]], assistant general counsel of the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] and the Waldemar A. Solf Professor of [[International Law]] at the [[United States Army]] Judge Advocate Generals School.\n\nCrane served as Professor of Practice at [[Syracuse University College of Law]] from 2006 until 2018.<ref>[http://law.syr.edu/news_events/news/professor-of-practice-david-m.-crane-l80-announces-retirement Professor of Practice David M. Crane L\u201980 Announces Retirement from the College of Law] [[Syracuse University College of Law]], press release of March 30, 2018.</ref> He taught international criminal law, international law, national security law, and the law of armed conflict.<ref name=\"David Crane\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beloit.edu/oie/campus_internat/crane.htm|title=David Crane|accessdate=2009-06-29}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"Professor of Practice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.law.syr.edu/faculty/facultymember.aspx?fac=152|title=David M. Crane - Professor of Practice|accessdate=2009-06-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609193355/http://law.syr.edu/faculty/facultymember.aspx?fac=152|archivedate=2010-06-09}}</ref>\n\nIn conjunction with Syracuse University College of Law students, Crane started [[Impunity Watch]], an online publication which seeks to inform the world of human rights violations in real-time. Another Syracuse University College of Law project is the Syria Accountability Project (SAP). SAP was begun in 2011 as a project of Crane\u2019s International Legal Practice course at SU Law and now involves 50 SU law students. SAP works collectively with several international organizations to provide impartial analysis of open source materials so that [[Bashar al-Assad|President Bashar al-Assad]] and his subordinates\u2014as well as members of the Syrian opposition\u2014can be prosecuted openly and fairly under the [[Geneva Conventions]], the [[Rome Statute]], and/or Syrian Penal Law.<ref name=\"dailyorange.com\">http://dailyorange.com/2013/10/professor-to-testify-about-syrian-war-crimes/</ref>\n\nFollowing his time as founding Chief Prosecutor of the Special Court for Sierra Leone, Crane and his fellow prosecutors DeSilva and [[Brenda Hollis]] traveled to [[The Hague]], [[Netherlands]] on September 26, 2013 to witness the upholding of Taylor\u2019s 50-year sentence by the special court\u2019s appeals judges.<ref>http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/26/world/africa/netherlands-charles-taylor-verdict/index.html?iref=allsearch</ref> On October 29, 2013 Crane testified in front of the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]] Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights, and International Organizations about the possible establishment of a Syrian War Crimes Tribunal.<ref name=\"dailyorange.com\"/> He later co-authored the [[2014 Syrian detainee report]].\n\nIn July 2018, the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] appointed Crane to co-chair (alongside [[Sara Hossain]] and [[Kaari Betty Murungi]]) a three-person Commission of Inquiry into the killing of at least 140 Palestinians by the Israeli army.<ref>Tom Miles (July 25, 2018), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-palestinans-un/u-n-picks-american-to-lead-investigation-into-gaza-protest-killings-idUSKBN1KF244 U.N. picks American to lead investigation into Gaza protest killings] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref> Already one month later, he resigned \u201cdue to a personal circumstance that has arisen.\u201d<ref>Toby Sterling (August 23, 2018), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-palestinians-un/chair-of-u-n-probe-of-gaza-violence-quits-less-than-month-into-job-idUSKCN1L811K Chair of U.N. probe of Gaza violence quits less than month into job] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190109000747/http://www.roberthjackson.org/ Robert H. Jackson Center], Chairman of the Board (2012-2015), Board Director (2012-present) \n* [[International Peace and Security Institute]], Member of the Board of Directors\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120427173235/http://www.sc-sl.org/ Special Court for Sierra Leone web site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130823212039/http://www.law.syr.edu/deans-faculty-staff/profile.aspx?fac=152 Syracuse University College of Law faculty listing and biography]\n*[http://legal.un.org/avl/faculty/Crane.html See forthcoming lectures in the Lecture Series of the United Nations Audiovisual Library of International Law]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crane, David}}\n[[Category:Special Court for Sierra Leone prosecutors]]\n[[Category:American lawyers]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University faculty]]\n[[Category:Ohio University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n",